<HTML>
<TITLE>FREE SPEECH DROWNS</TITLE>
<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<P>
<H2>FREE SPEECH DROWNS<BR>
IN THE WAKE OF THE PC NAVY </H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
<CENTER>
<I>by</I>
<P>
<I>Robert L. Maginnis</I></CENTER>
<P>
The Navy has become so politically correct (PC) since the Tailhook
debacle that now sailors can't even express their opinion about
a controversial policy.
<P>
Last August, Navy pilot Lt. Cmdr. Kenneth Carkhuff told his boss
that he objected to women serving in combat and that his views
were based on religious convictions. As a result, Carkhuff was
removed from his unit and now faces dismissal for failing to &quot;demonstrate
leadership.&quot;
<P>
Since when does expressing an opinion translate into a leadership
failure? According to the Navy, Carkhuff's disagreement with its
full-steam-ahead women in combat policy warrants a discharge without
benefits after 13 years of outstanding service.
<P>
Carkhuff believes that women should not be subjected to the violence
of combat. His religiously-motivated beliefs are shared by many
less vocal members of the military who understand that PC reigns
and stating a contrary belief is grounds for dismissal.
<P>
This case is really about Constitutionally guaranteed free speech.
During the Second World War the Supreme Court heard a case involving
religiously based speech. In <I>Barnette v. West Virginia State
Board of Education</I>, the high court found that education authorities
could not force a Jehovah's Witness to pledge allegiance to the
American flag. The court ruled that, &quot;Freedom to differ is
not limited to things that do not matter.&quot;
<P>
Women in combat matters to Cmdr. Carkhuff because it's contrary
to his religious beliefs. The 34-year-old Naval Academy graduate
does not dispute the Navy's authority to place women in combat,
but he respectfully disagrees and exercised his Constitutional
right to express that opinion privately.
<P>
The Clinton Administration has erased more than 250,000 combat
exemptions for women. Today, women can serve in 95 percent of
all Navy billets. Feminists say this is progress, but combat veterans
and our combat-hardened allies know this portends future disaster.
<P>
In 1992, uniformed female military officers descended on Capitol
Hill to lobby against the female combat ban labeling it an &quot;equal
opportunity&quot; issue. The

Pentagon ignored the regulations which restrict uniformed sailors
from lobbying.
<P>
These women won their fight. But in contrast, when a lone man
objects to the same radical changes, suddenly an anchor from Washington
drops on his berth threatening to sink him along with his wife
and five children.
<P>
Cmdr. Carkhuff was assigned to an SH60B Seahawk unit which had
five pilots; two were female. He disagreed with the Navy's women-in-combat
policy but agreed to fly with female pilots if ordered. His boss
chose the PC route and booted Carkhuff overboard.
<P>
On January 25th, the Chief of Naval Personnel sent Carkhuff a
letter charging him with &quot;substandard performance&quot; and
failure to demonstrate leadership for not supporting the Navy's
female policy. A board of three Naval captains will soon determine
his fate.
<P>
The issue for Congress is whether the Navy has so embraced political
correctness that it no longer stands by objective truth. Sample
evidence of the Navy's ongoing PC revolution.
<UL>
<LI>Top admiral Jeremy Boorda made one of his first visits to Capitol
Hill a session with Rep. Patricia Schroeder (D-Co.) -- Tailhook's
grand inquisitor -- and promised to do better. He now oversees
the rapid feminization of the Navy.
<P>
<LI>Three top admirals -- Kelso, Arthur and Mauz -- suffered direct
hits from unsubstantiated feminist accusations. These wounded
warriors were put to sea by the PC Navy.
<P>
<LI> The Navy deceived the public about the pregnancy problem aboard
the first aircraft carrier with women. Five pregnancies became
29 and the count is still climbing.
<P>
<LI>The Navy wrote a pregnancy policy that all but endorses abortion
and takes no position on out-of-wedlock births much less pregnancies
that result from extramarital affairs. But two-thirds of all uniformed,
one-time mothers have never been married and more than half of
all pregnant women who abandon ship never return.
<P>
<LI>The Navy hosted &quot;Diversity Day '94&quot; last September
which was attended by six PC admirals and included seminars that
promoted homosexuality as the moral equivalent of heterosexuality.
<P>
<LI>The Navy leads the services in the number of open homosexuals
serving. This violates the military homosexual law signed by President
Clinton in 1993.</UL>
<P>
The Clinton Administration's decision to place more women in combat
is not based on military necessity. It is a political decision
to buy feminist favor and in time it will backfire. In the meantime,
we must pretend.
<P>
Cmdr. Carkhuff should be awarded a medal for declaring the &quot;emperor
has no clothes.&quot; 
Instead, the Pentagon's PC crowd is working overtime ridding the
Navy of people of character who dare oppose a misguided policy.
<P>
<CENTER>***</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Robert Maginnis is a policy analyst with the Family Research
Council, Washington, D.C. and a retired Army officer who graduated
from the Naval Postgraduate School.</I> 

<p>

