<html>
<title>SHANNON FAULKNER IS GONE</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<p>
<h2>FAULKNER IS GONE, BUT<br>
BATTLE OVER SINGLE-SEX<br>
SCHOOLS THREATENS<br>
EDUCATIONAL DIVERSITY</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>
<p>
Shannon Faulkner's decision to quit The Citadel does not stop
the battle over state-sponsored same-sex education.  That controversy
won't even be resolved when a federal judge decides whether an
alternative for women at Converse College in Spartanburg, S.C.
eliminates the need for a co-ed Citadel program, and daily reports
of Faulkner replacements or other touching profiles of military
women won't change the issue.  The gender assault goes much farther.
<P>
The Clinton Justice Department will take this case to the Supreme
Court and the high court could strike down public funded single-gender
education forever -- damaging America's academic diversity.  That
is a serious threat.
<P>
The Citadel's loss of the Faulkner trial would threaten the more
than 80 all-women's colleges that depend on taxpayer support.
That's why some of these colleges have expressed their support
for The Citadel in amicus briefs.  Their fear is that prohibitions
against direct funding of single-sex educational institutions
would lead to prohibitions against &quot;indirect funding&quot;
of single-sex colleges through federal financial aid and tax exemptions.
 This would make it difficult for any single-sex educational institution
to survive.
<P>
A diversified educational system should include single-sex schools
because same-gender settings are best for some students.  The
benefits of single-sex schools for some students are marked. 
Students do better academically, and women tend to pursue majors
in science, math and management, hold more leadership positions,
and are more likely to seek higher academic degrees.  Both genders
are more likely to participate in
honors programs and pursue careers in business, law or teaching,
and both sexes tend to find their overall academic experience
more rewarding.
<P>
One argument raised by critics of single-sex educational institutions
is that schools like The Citadel exacerbate the bias against women.
 But over the past 20 years there has been a dramatic increase
in the educational attainment of women in this country.  Diane
Ravitch, a former assistant secretary of education in the Bush
Administration, reports that:  67 percent of women high school
graduates go to college, compared to 58 percent of men; 55 percent
of all college undergraduates are women; women earn 59 percent
of all master's degrees; and women earn 39 percent of all doctoral
degrees, up from 14 percent in 1970.
<P>
Besides enhancing academic diversity, single-sex education can
help curb the epidemic of youth violence.  Same-gender schools
have emerged as a means to help at-risk inner city boys -- especially
those in elementary school.
<P>
Same-sex settings give boys a greater chance to succeed in life.
 Boys learn most when they perceive their teacher as a disciplinarian
and competitor.  They respond better to teaching based on the
adversary model of education, which incorporates contest and competition
in a disciplined environment.  And male teachers provide possibly
the only male role model alternative to a street gang leader for
some inner-city boys.  
<P>
Single-sex schools for girls have a positive academic effect and
protect them from aggressive boys.  They have better affective
outcomes and higher test scores.  They also enjoy higher self-esteem
than their co-ed peers.
<P>
Studies have shown that single-gender education works in the inner
city.  Seventh graders who had attended the Malcolm X Academy
in Detroit, an all-boys inner city school, had the highest math
scores among 77 Detroit schools and the second highest in Michigan
among 780 schools.
<P>
Cornelius Riordan, a professor at Providence University, found
that African-American and Hispanic students in single-gender schools
outperformed their coed peers by nearly a grade level.  And inner
city single-mothers recognize the value of same-sex schools, especially
for boys.
<P>
Unfortunately, single-gender public schools are illegal because
they allegedly discriminate based on gender.   Groups like the
American Civil Liberties Union and the National Organization of
Women have threatened to file lawsuits claiming a violation of
Title IX of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.  These are the same groups
which lined-up behind Shannon Faulkner's fight with The Citadel.
<P>
Some critics of single-sex education compare policies that exclude
because of gender to policies that discriminate according to race.
 They contend that the issues involved in The Citadel case are
the same as those in the 1954 Supreme Court case of <I>Brown v.
Board of Education</I>.  But this is a false analogy.
<P>
Gender differences are very different from racial differences.
 In some parts of the country, races were once segregated on public
transportation, in schools and in bathrooms.  But when racial
segregation finally ended, beneficial forms of segregation by
gender continued.  We continue to have &quot;separate but equal&quot;
male and female public bathrooms because most people recognize
that gender is different than race.
<P>
The battle over state-funded single-sex classes is not about bigotry
and is not a civil rights &quot;retreat.&quot;  The truth is single-gender
schools diversify America's educational experience and provide
wider options to individuals -- both women and men -- that might
benefit greatly from them.   They also give constructive male
role models to fatherless boys growing up in inner-cities.
<P>
-- 8/22/95
<P>
<center>***</center>
<P>
<I>Robert Maginnis is a policy analyst with the Family Research
Council, a research and advocacy organization based in Washington,
DC.</I>

