<html>
<title>AMERICA AND THE SELLING OF PEDOPHILIA</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>AMERICA AND THE SELLING OF<br>
PEDOPHILIA</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Robert Knight and Cathleen Cleaver</i></center>
<p>
Calvin Klein pulled its kiddie porn ads from the market this week,
but not before millions of Americans were treated to a new low
in the ongoing campaign to sexualize children. 
<P>
One ad features a young blonde teen-ager on the floor of a cheaply
furnished room. Her panties are exposed under a short skirt. 
She looks like a kidnap victim, about to be raped.  Her eyes convey
hurt and fear.  Another photo shows a boy clad in purple underpants.
His nails are painted black.  His eyes convey lust.  The ads were
shot by the same photographer that did Madonna's pornographic
book, <U>Sex.</U>
<P>
The television ads are even more suggestive.   In fact, the TV
ads are eerily similar to tapes that were the center of the controversy
last year when the Clinton Justice Department tried to weaken
the definition of child pornography.  In the <I>U.S. v. Knox</I>
case, Janet Reno argued that children had to be completely nude
for material to be considered child pornography, and furthermore,
that the children had to be purposely acting lasciviously.  The
material in <I>Knox</I> was videotapes produced by the Nather
Company, which described them as &quot;erotic beyond belief,&quot;
containing &quot;tender&quot; teens and pre-teens in &quot;savage&quot;
panty shots.  The Nather Tapes were found by the courts to be
child pornography, a verdict agreed to by the U.S. Senate, which
voted 100-0 to  condemn the Reno interpretation.  
<P>
Like the Calvin Klein ads, Nather Tape Two opens with images of
a clothed adolescent girl tentatively striking poses, responding
to off-camera directions from an adult male voice.  The camera
repeatedly focuses on her panties.  At one point, she says, &quot;I
don't know what to do.&quot;  The off-camera voice asks her to
sit down and push her knees up.  Another panty shot follows, and
another voice off camera says, &quot;We love it.&quot;  In another
tape, the off-camera voice asks a pre-teen girl to dance as the
camera focuses on parts of her body.  In the Calvin Klein ads,
a teen girl stands nervously in a basement room, responding to
off-camera directions from an adult male voice.  The off-camera
voice asks why she's nervous.  She 
replies,  &quot;I don't know what you're going to do.&quot;  The
voice asks her if she's a good dancer.  When she replies that
she is, he asks her to dance for him.  Other ads show a boy in
t-shirt and jeans.  The off-camera voice compliments the boy on
his body, and tells him he looks strong.  The voice then goads
him to prove his strength by ripping his t-shirt open, and the
boy complies.  The similarity between the porn tapes and the Klein
ads is uncanny.        
<P>
Before public pressure forced Klein to shelve the ads, many Americans
watched in dismay, asking how a nation came to allow its children
to be fodder for crude commercials by unscrupulous vendors.  Then
again, some ask, why has America allowed its children to be exposed
to graphic materials in public schools in the name of  &quot;AIDS
prevention&quot; and  &quot;sex education?&quot; 
<P>
The sexualization of children in America had its beginnings not
on a Madison Avenue drawing board or even in Hollywood but in
the pages of one of the best-known (and least-read) books of the
century -- Alfred C. Kinsey's <U>Sexual Behavior in the Human
Male</U>.  In 1948, Kinsey, an Indiana University zoologist, shocked
the world with the publication of  what came to be known as the
Kinsey Report.  A companion volume on females was published in
1953.
<P>
Both books ignited a controversy that persists to this day.  Both
paint a picture of people of all ages awash in secret sexual experimentation.
 The Kinsey Reports formed the &quot;scientific&quot; basis of
Hugh Hefner's destructive Playboy Philosophy, which brought pornography,
adultery, pre-marital and homosexual sex into the American mainstream.

<P>
But the most disturbing element of the Kinsey Reports is the overlooked
chapter in the male volume entitled &quot;Early Sexual Growth
and Activity.&quot;   Featuring charts in which &quot;trained
persons&quot; measured incidences of &quot;orgasm&quot; in children
as young as two months, the Kinsey child sex material contains
the seeds of a growing cultural movement to regard children as
not only sexually viable but entitled to sex with adults.  
<P>
In 1981, Dr. Judith Reisman delivered a paper on the Kinsey child
sexuality data at the Fifth World Congress of Sexuality in Jerusalem.
 Nine years later, Dr. Reisman, along with sex therapist Edward
W. Eichel,  research physician Dr. J. Gordon Muir and psychologist
Dr. John Court wrote <U>Kinsey, Sex and Fraud: The Indoctrination
of a People</U>.   The authors, according to the British medical
journal <I>The Lancet</I>, &quot;demolish the foundations of the
two [Kinsey] reports.&quot;   They also expose the foundation
of the Kinsey philosophy, which views all sexual acts as essentially
equal &quot;outlets.&quot;  To Kinsey, the sex between a husband
and wife is no different morally, physically or socially from
that of  sex between the same genders, between children and adults,
or even between humans and animals.  
<P>
And to Kinsey, age is not much of a factor.  In the Female volume,
he remarks, &quot; It is difficult to understand why a child,
except for its cultural conditioning, should be disturbed at having
its genitalia touched.&quot; 
<P>
 
<P>
Since the Kinsey books remain the most influential works in the
study of sex, their philosophy has spilled over, first to academia,
then to the larger culture.  Kinsey disciples went on to found
the Sex Information and Education Council of the United States
(SIECUS), which peddles the Kinsey philosophy in its sex education
materials.  In 1980, SIECUS co-founder Mary Calderone told the
Association of Planned Parenthood Physicians that SIECUS' primary
mission was to educate society &quot;very broadly and deeply with
awareness of the vital importance of infant and childhood sexuality.&quot;
 SIECUS President Debra Haffner has even envisioned a &quot;national
petting project,&quot; in which young teens are taught how to
stimulate each other sexually -- without having intercourse. 
With such novel approaches, SIECUS recently snagged a major federal
grant from the Clinton Administration to evaluate all sex education
programs in the United States.  
<P>
In 1991, <I>Child</I> magazine featured an article by then-Kinsey
Institute President June Reinisch called &quot;Sensuality and
Kids.&quot;  Reinisch counsels parents to foster sex play and
masturbation among children because it &quot;develops self-esteem&quot;
and for which some children &quot;use to relax and get ready for
sleep.&quot;  In the same vein, former Surgeon General Joycelyn
Elders advocated teaching children to masturbate. 
<P>
Other signs that the Kinsey philosophy is destroying cultural
protections for children abound:
<UL>
<LI>The American Psychiatric Association's latest <U>Diagnostic
and Statistical Manual</U> has redefined pedophilia so that a
person who molests children is no longer a &quot;pedophile&quot;
unless he feels bad or anxious about what he is doing.   The &quot;stress&quot;
triggered by feeling bad is now considered the marker for a paraphilic
disorder.  So a well-adjusted molester is okay because he feels
okay about what he does.
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>In <I>The New Republic</I>, the mainstream liberal political
weekly, Hanna Rosin offers a defense of the pro-pedophile North
American Man-Boy Love Association in a recent review of the documentary
film <I>Chickenhawks</I>.  Regarding sex between boys and men,
she asks, &quot;is the idea of mutual consent so absurd?&quot;
 Then she quotes a NAMBLA member who advocates treating children
&quot;in a different way.&quot;  Rosin's comment:  &quot;Certainly
a self-serving view, but still plausibly on the continuum of,
say, a defense of children's legal autonomy.&quot; 
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><I>The New York Times </I>devoted several pages in its Sunday
magazine last year to Sally Mann's &quot;provocative&quot; nude
photos of her own children.  This week, incidentally, the Times'
fashion supplement includes a MAC Viva Glam lipstick ad with a
spread-legged crotch shot of a leather-stockinged Ru Paul, the
transvestite. The paper still carries this phrase on its banner:
 &quot;All the news that's fit to print.&quot;
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Movies and television increasingly portray children as sexual
actors.  In the 1994 film <I>Milk Money</I>, for example, young
boys watch and sell pornographic videos and pool their milk money
to buy the services of a prostitute.  In the film <I>Blank Check</I>,
a preadolescent boy schemes to have sex with a woman twice his
age. A Disney affiliate, Miramax,  has released an NC-17 film,
<I>Kids</I>, which shows young teens indulging in indiscriminate
sex and drug-taking.  The film's makers frankly admit that their
work is perverse, and that its gritty tone might offend some people.
 Precisely.  And have you noticed how often young children now
emit vulgarities and obscenities, even in &quot;family films?&quot;
</UL>
<P>
As for Calvin Klein, the designer rebukes the charges against
his filthy ads, saying that he was not intending a pornographic
message.  Klein says that &quot;some people are taking away a
different perception&quot; of the ads than the &quot;intended
message.&quot;   Coming from the man who began high-fashion kiddie
porn back in 1980 when he had 15-year-old Brooke Shields say suggestively
that &quot;nothing&quot; came between her and her Calvins, this
does not pass the straight face test.  He is lying, or is so personally
corrupt that he is unable to recognize the depravity of his own
message.  In a full-page ad in <I>The New York Times</I>, Klein
defended the ads, describing their &quot;positive message&quot;
as &quot;that young people today, the most media savvy generation
yet, have a real strength of character and independence.  They
have very strongly defined lines of what they will and will not
do -- and have a great ability to know who they are and who they
want to be.&quot;  Pretty rhetoric, and very similar to that employed
 by the North American Man-Boy Love Association, which contends
that children ought to be &quot;independent&quot; and &quot;make
their own decisions&quot; about having sex with adults.  The nice
men at NAMBLA want to &quot;empower&quot; children.  Talk about
&quot;the Hurried Child.&quot;   The child-sex movement is all
too eager to &quot;free&quot; children from the constraints of
their parents' morality.
<P>
Certain features of the Klein photo ads scream of child pornography.
 The off-color carpet and wood paneling suggest a basement room
-- child molesters often use the seclusion and privacy of a basement
to photograph their victims.  The blonde girl in the ad has a
frightened look on her face, and her hand is raised to her mouth,
where her lips appear slightly blue.  When children are sodomized,
they are often left bruised. 
<P>
Between Alfred Kinsey, Calvin Klein, and their disciples in Hollywood,
the entire nation is getting bruised -- beginning with our children.
<P>
-- 8/29/95
<P>
<center>***</center>
<P>
<I>Robert Knight, Director of Cultural Studies for the Family
Research Council, wrote and  directed</i> The Children of Table
34, <i>a new documentary about Alfred Kinsey.  Cathleen Cleaver,
Legal Director for the Family Research Council, has litigated
pornography cases for her former employer, the National Law Center
for Children and Families.</I>

<p>

