</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>PARENTAL RIGHTS: WHOSE CHILDREN ARE THEY?</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>PARENTAL RIGHTS:</br>
WHOSE CHILDREN ARE THEY?</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Cathleen Cleaver, Esq.</i></center>
<p>
Congress will soon take up legislation designed to acknowledge
(or restore) the right of parents to direct the upbringing and
education of their children.  Is federal legislation really necessary?
 Consider the following:  This summer, Mr. and Mrs. Waymon Earls
of Toccoa, Georgia were shocked to find a bag of condoms in their
13- and 15-year-old daughters' room.  The girls confessed that
their middle school counselor had helped them get the condoms.
After repeatedly being told that it was none of the parent's business,
a reluctant school superintendent revealed to the Earls that the
counselor had driven the girls during school hours to a health
clinic where they were tested for AIDS and cervical cancer, and
given condoms and prescriptions for birth control pills.  The
school has, to date,  refused to give the Earls the results of
the tests.  &quot;We're simply trying to do what's best for the
students,&quot; said the superintendent.  The Earls have filed
a lawsuit against the school and its officials. Georgia taxpayers
are funding the school's defense, and its attorneys have moved
the case to federal court.
<p>
Education bureaucrats are not the only culprits.  A steady drumbeat
of Child Protective Services tragedies reveals an increasing nonchalance
about the sanctity of the family unit on the part of government
social workers who take children from their homes on little more
than rumor.  This &quot;loot first and ask questions later&quot;
approach reflects the height of arrogance, and does untold damage
to the very souls CPS was designed to protect.  Tragically, however,
there are real cases of intra-family abuse and neglect.  But in
too many such cases, protective government agencies completely
fail to intervene.   That our child protection system needs improvement
is apparent, but no case of under-enforcement can support a blanket
sanction of over-enforcement so obtrusive as to be self-defeating.
<p>
To compound matters, President Clinton earlier this year agreed
to the United Nation's Convention on the Rights of the Child,
which espouses the &quot;new concept&quot; of government &quot;protecting
children from the power of parents.&quot;  There is little doubt that the 
United Nations is out of touch with American ideas.  The U.N.'s Convention on
the Rights of the Child was telling, but the platform document
for its Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing -- with its
confusion about gender and hostility toward motherhood and natural
families -- cinches the case.  The UN has been virtually co-opted
by social experimentalists who can test theories in an ostensibly
reputable body where physical and conceptual &quot;foreign-ness&quot;
makes for reduced scrutiny and no real accountability.  Paternal
deconstruction proponents responsible for the Convention on the
Rights of the Child have accomplished through the U.N. what they
could not through the legislative process.
<p>
Senator Charles Grassley and Congressman Steve Largent have introduced
the Parental Rights and Responsibilities Act of 1995.  The Act
establishes the fundamental right of parents to direct and provide
for the education and religious teaching of their children, and
also addresses health care decisions and reasonable corporal discipline.
 Importantly, the Act allows the government to intervene when
it has a compelling interest to do so, and has specific allowances
for child abuse and neglect.  
<p>
The notion that government should protect children from the power
of parents is opposed by the vast majority of Americans.  In February
of this year, Luntz Research asked registered voters nationwide:
&quot;Who do you feel should be primarily responsible for the
upbringing and education of children -- parents or the government?&quot;
 Voters favored parents by a landslide 94%.
<p>
The Earls will continue to fight for the right to be parents,
and pro-family groups will rally around the much-needed Parental
Rights Act.  Stable, intact families rearing children with both
love and direction have never been in shorter supply or more desperately
needed.  The time has come to put a stop to efforts to replace
Mom and Dad with Big Brother.
<p>
--9/20/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<I>Cathleen A. Cleaver, Esq. is the Director of Legal Studies
at the Family Research Council, a Washington, DC-based research
and advocacy organization.</I>

