<title>Observations About America's Welfare Crisis</title>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>OBSERVATIONS ABOUT<br>
AMERICA'S WELFARE CRISIS</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Jennifer E. Marshall</i></center>
<p>
<li><b>On Responsibility.</b> For a man to enjoy freedom,
he must accept responsibility for his own acts.  The failure to
accept responsibility denies man basic human dignity.
<p>
The problem with the welfare system is that it suppresses a sense
of personal responsibility and negates freedom and dignity in
the bargain.
<p>
The system neither demands nor rewards responsible behavior. 
Instead, it pays benefits to those who spurn virtue and, in so
doing, makes a mockery of responsible citizens.
<p>
Franklin D. Roosevelt said that &quot;welfare is a narcotic, a
subtle destroyer of the human spirit,&quot; and Alexander Hamilton
observed that &quot;a power over a man's subsistence amounts to
a power over his will.&quot;
<p>
By creating a culture of dependency, we have reduced a potentially
proud and independent people to passive clients.  We have told
them, not that they are equal to the inevitable challenges of
life, but that they are helpless -- a different, less human kind
of breed than the rest of us who can and do live by the rules.
<p>
Welfare bureaucrats say, &quot;You can't do this.  Let us do it
for you.  And pay us to do it with your vote, year after year.&quot;
 And so we are empowering the bureaucracy at the same time we
are destroying individuals, and children are inheriting not only
material poverty but their parents' poverty of the spirit.
<p>
<li><b>On Compassion.</b> The problem of the 1990s is no
longer &quot;poverty,&quot; but, rather, &quot;dependency.&quot;
 And the problem of dependency is primarily a moral problem.
<p>
Government policy that provides money to the poor, while encouraging
them to act in ways that ensure dependency, is not compassionate.
 That's &quot;compassion&quot; that kills, and even liberals have
begun to see the light.
<p>
In a December 15, 1986 article in <i>The New Republic</i>, liberal
social critic Mickey Kaus admitted that &quot;compassion . . .
is a miserable basis for liberal politics.  It carries the unmistakable
implication of dependence and piteousness on the part of those
on the receiving end of the sentiment. . . .  [I]t provides no
principle to tell us when our abstract compassionate impulses
should stop . . . which is why a politics based on mass-produced
compassion leads naturally to the indiscriminate dispensing of
cash.&quot;
<p>
Compassion instead must be defined as the potential to effect
change in the current system -- because the current system is
synonymous with misery.
<p>
And the principle behind that change must be a new sense of limits,
based on the discrimination between good and bad behavior.
<p>
In her book <i>Poverty and Compassion</i>, Gertrude Himmelfarb
suggested that we must be determined, not just to feel good about
ourselves, but to do good to others.  And sometimes it is necessary
to feel bad ourselves and to curb our run-away compassion, in
order to serve the best interests of others.
<p>
<li><b>On Illegitimacy.</b> Can we doubt that a system
that subsidizes illegitimacy perpetuates illegitimacy -- and creates
social chaos?  Listen to the testimony of one woman on welfare,
quoted in the March 1995 <i>Reader's Digest</i>:  &quot;Welfare
is an enabler.  It's not that you want to be in that situation.
 But it's there.  We always know.&quot;  
<p>
In other words, welfare enables unmitigated disaster -- by making
it increasingly difficult for the poor to make the right choices
which they otherwise are fully capable of making.  
<p>
Welfare destroys individuals first, and then the destruction moves
outward in concentric circles to consume the entire community.
 When illegitimacy reaches a critical mass -- as it already has
in many communities, both black and white -- the neighborhood
effects create problems that extend far beyond the recipients
of welfare.
<p>
Community values and the norms for male
behavior are changed, and with them the behavior of young men
and women who never touch an AFDC check.  Thus, the effect
of those checks springs not only from discrete changes in economic
incentives but from a larger, more pervasive effect on the formation
of character among poor young people.
<p>
Great Society programs shared a common assumption:  that the poor
are victims in the grip of larger forces.  We are all victims
now, of large destructive forces of our own making -- and no one
is more victimized than the poor themselves.
<p>
<li><b>On Family Formation.</b> By subsidizing illegitimacy,
we have turned our inner cities into a wasteland.  And we can't
expect to roll back the tide until we discover some means to ensure
that more children grow up with a father in the home.
<p>
Families socialize children, and persons of a utopian bent of
mind are wrong in thinking that we can replace the family by some
kind of government construct that will accomplish the same ends.
 We have tried that, and we have failed miserably.
<p>
Liberals made their mistake in assuming that virtues like selflessness
and generosity are a part of human nature.  To the contrary, any
right impulse that man possesses must take shape and form within
the family -- or else it will not form at all.
<p>
Even <i>Newsweek</i> has announced that &quot;the name of the
game is shame,&quot; but shame springs up spontaneously only when
children experience loving family relationships that make them
care about how their actions will impact those around them.  Children
who don't feel the love of family can't feel remorse.  They just
feel the pain that inevitably results from violating the laws
of society and of &quot;Nature's God.&quot;
<p>
And so, for the sake of the children, we are justified in taking
whatever means are available to a free people to ensure that intact
families are once again the norm.
<p>
If we don't take action, one of every 2 babies will be born to
a single mother within the next 20 years.  That's a fact we can't
live with.
<P>
<li><b>On Cultural Decline.</b> Peggy Noonan has said that
we have all had a moment when we suddenly realized that the world
was changing before our very eyes -- and not for the better. 
For her, the moment came at a graduation ceremony when the audience
stood up and applauded a senior who would soon give birth to a
baby minus a father.
<p>
Noonan wrote in the September 14, 1992 issue of <i>Forbes</i>:
 &quot;In the sound of that applause I heard a wall falling, a
thousand-year wall, a wall of sanctions that said: We as a society
do not approve of teenaged unwed motherhood because it is not
good for the child, not good for the mother, and not good for
us.&quot;
<p>
What we applaud, we encourage; and we do a grave disservice to
young women and their children when we refuse to draw lines between
right and wrong.
<p>
We can disapprove and yet still provide help -- but we cannot
make that critical distinction by guaranteeing a right to cash
benefits independent of the obligation to good conduct.
<p>
The only real help comes from private individuals and organizations
that sponsor moral renewal at the same time they offer material
support.  Since it's far easier to receive a check in the mail,
no questions asked, welfare denies its dependents the chance to
get real help -- the kind of help that changes lives.
<p>
<li><b>On The Needs of Our Children.</b> James Q. Wilson
said in the 1994 Wriston Lecture at the Manhattan Institute that,
rather than focusing on how to reduce poverty or dependency, we
must set our sights on saving the children.
<p>
We must focus on the dictum that, for a child to thrive, he needs
the &quot;irrational involvement&quot; of two parents who love
him fiercely.
<p>
The problem is that a teenage mother is still a child herself,
with all the distractions and conflicting emotions of adolescence
at play.
<p>
She must contend not only with earaches and two-year-old tantrums,
but with her own broken dreams of any realistic chance at a better
life.
<p>
Three-fourths of illegitimate births among whites alone are to
women with a high school education or less; and, the younger the
single mother, the less likely she is to finish high school.
<p>
The kindest policy we could adopt is one that ensures that young
unwed mothers will have to live either at home with their families
or in group homes.  Not only would the young mother have the help
and supervision of adults on a daily basis, but her child would
be far less likely to suffer abuse or neglect.
<p>
Children born out of wedlock are statistically much more likely
to be abused.  And it is alone at night in an empty apartment
that a tired young mother is most likely to react with anger at
the sound of a crying baby.
<p>
Studies show that the high rate of out-of-wedlock births to young
mothers is the primary explanation for America's low international
standing on measures of infant mortality.
<p>
If we really want to end the suffering of children, we should
end the government subsidies that enable children to bear children.
<P>
<li><b>On Fatherlessness.</b> More than 70% of all juveniles
in state reform institutions come from fatherless homes.  The
likelihood that a young male will engage in criminal activities
doubles if he is raised without a father and triples if he lives
in a neighborhood with a high concentration of single-parent families.
<p>
While shocking, the statistics should not take us completely by
surprise.  Young males are a problematic sex, and they require
socialization that only fathers can provide.
<p>
If not socialized into responsible adult behavior and, as it turns
out, into responsible sexual behavior, young men are dangerous.
 Social scientists are just now beginning to say, in their bloodless
way, what policemen have known for years -- in a <i>not</i> so
bloodless way.
<p>
It is not enough to say that certain kinds of welfare reforms
will cause suffering.  We have to come to terms with the degree
of suffering that's occurring right now.
<p>
And we have to include in the body count the number of children
who fall prey to the violent crime that results from, as James
Q. Wilson put it, &quot;neglecting the processes by which the
underclass reproduces itself.&quot;
<p>
We can maintain our broad legal freedoms -- and our lives -- <i>only</i>
if we manage to instill in our children a degree of self-restraint.
 And we can cultivate that restraint only by turning the hearts
of the fathers to the children.
<p>
<li><b>On Building Community.</b> The welfare system does
not represent the intended relation of free and equal citizens.
 In fact, welfare practically precludes <i>any</i> relationship
between rich and poor.
<p>
Benefit checks amount to essentially tribute money.  In exchange
for our money, we ask that the poor simply leave us alone.
<p>
We hope that the state will make them comfortable, but the paying
of checks by an impersonal bureaucracy requires no personal
involvement on our part.
<p>
Do we realize the implications?
<p>
We have reinstituted segregation -- though not along lines of
race -- because the underclass culture fosters alienation.  Already
we are divided by the distance between &quot;middle-class&quot;
values and the moral anarchy of the inner city, and we will find
it increasingly appealing to create a modern analogue of the Indian
reservation to house the people we fear.
<p>
Our hope lies in the private transactions in which we meet individuals
in need of help, not as clients, but as fellow human beings. 
Tocqueville explained: &quot;Private charity establishes valuable
ties between the rich and the poor by involving the giver in the
fate of the one whose poverty he has undertaken to alleviate.
 Although divided by circumstance, they are willingly reconciled.&quot;
<p>
This is a country badly in need of healing, not of new and deeper
divisions.  But we will have to change welfare if we want to stymie
the secession of the poor from middle-class life -- and from the
common experience of freedom, as the Founders meant it.
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Jennifer E. Marshall is a policy analyst specializing in welfare
reform at the Family Research Council, a Washington, DC-based
research and advocacy organization.</i>

<p>

