<html>
<title>THE LEGACY OF THE NEW JERSEY FAMILY CAP</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>THE LEGACY OF THE NEW JERSEY<br>
FAMILY CAP:</h2>
<h4>A BLUEPRINT FOR THE STATES</h4></center>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<center><i>by<br>
Jennifer E. Marshall</i></center>
<p>
When the states begin to reassess welfare policy in the wake of
new federal legislation, the defining issue will be the family
cap.  A well-rounded debate over the family cap will ask and answer
fundamental questions about the future of social policy in a post-entitlement
world -- and few questions beg right answers quite so urgently.
<p>
A modest first step, the family cap would simply deny an increase
in the AFDC cash benefits to mothers who bear additional children
while on welfare.  The &quot;restriction&quot; is scant in proportion
to the scale of devastation wrought by open-ended checks.
<p>
In many instances, those checks have reduced the birth father
to no more than a passing stranger, and marriage is teetering
on the brink of anachronism in communities with a high concentration
of welfare recipients.  To the extent that the state provides
ready alternatives, marriage, work, and self-sufficiency will
inevitably seem a little less hallowed, a little less than necessary.
<p>
The purpose of the family cap is, not to reduce births per se,
but to restore a sense of personal responsibility by insisting
that families on welfare live by the same values and confront
exactly the same choices as the general population.  The working
poor, for example, receive no increase in salary when another
child is added to the family.  Lowering our expectations of a
woman on welfare and the father of her child is no different from
lowering our estimation of their capability -- implying that they
are a different, less human kind of breed than the rest of us
who can and do live by the rules.
<p>
In his 1988 book <I>In Pursuit of Happiness and Good Government</I>,
Charles Murray argues that self-respect is an essential human
need and that the threshold condition for self-respect is accepting
responsibility for one's own life.  Self-determination must be
authentic, however.  An &quot;as if&quot; condition does not suffice.
Thus, Murray concludes, &quot;self-respect is not within the gift of any 
government or any policy. . . .  The only thing that government can do is
provide an environment within which people can earn their self-respect&quot;[1]
by earning their own way in the world.  If children are suffering
because parents are irresponsible, no amount of government money
can allay the suffering -- because the parents will still be irresponsible.
<p>
But Murray also defines self-respect as &quot;measuring up to
internalized standards of what it means to be a full-fledged member
of the community.&quot;[2] Government policy that dumbs down the
standards for welfare recipients so that &quot;measuring up&quot;
no longer has any content, or makes any economic sense, does violence
to the human spirit.  It's also singularly unjust.  Women on welfare
should have equal opportunity to follow the playbook that for
centuries has been the surest guarantor of human happiness.  What
Edmund Burke wrote long ago is even more true today: &quot;We
know that we have made no discoveries, and we think that no discoveries
are to be made, in morality.&quot;  Yet, we perpetuate a welfare
system that makes it harder for men and women to pursue virtuous
living.
<p>
Arguments against the current system rest not on value premises
exclusively but on empirical fact, confirmed by social science
data, that adult satisfaction depends on earning one's own way
and that children's well-being depends critically on a stable
family life.[3]  A proper concept of justice places a premium, not
on securing any particular material result, but on upholding the
social agreement that men and women work for their bread and wait
to bear children until they are emotionally and financially able
to provide for their support.  Certainly, we should question the
justice of requiring working men and women to uphold the rules
while spending their hard-earned tax dollars to subsidize the
systematic violation of those rules.
<p>
The central problem with the welfare system is that it deranges
social expectations regarding work and marriage by turning nature's
rewards and penalties on end.  Asserting that everyone possesses
moral autonomy is not the same as asserting that everyone possesses
equal capacity to sort through the mixed signals of a policy that
obliterates natural consequences and denies virtue its full reward
by making crimes against the social compact pay.
<p>
Again, however, the argument for the family cap rests, not on
value premises alone, but on certain assumptions about human nature
and social causation that are empirically verifiable.  And the
most recent data from New Jersey's experiment with the family
cap provide powerful evidence that proponents of the cap are indeed
correct in their assumptions.
<p>
In the sixteen months after the family cap took effect in August
of 1993, the average monthly birth rate for women on AFDC in New
Jersey declined by 10 percent or more -- a durable, sizable, and
real reduction in the birth rate.[4] When the denominator is restricted
to women of childbearing age (15-45 years old), whose youngest
child is at least 10 months old and who have been on AFDC for
at least 12 months, the reported birth rate decreased by 17.6
percent over the 12-month period immediately following implementation
of the Family Development Program (FDP).[5]
<p>
While the time series data is significant, the most interesting
piece of evidence to date surfaced in a memo leaked to the press
from the formal evaluation study at Rutgers University.  According
to the memo, the Rutgers study has found no significant difference
in the rate of births to women in the &quot;experimental&quot;
group, who are subject to the restriction on additional cash benefits,
and women in the &quot;control&quot; group, who are exempt from
the cash limitation.
<p>
<b>Contrary to press reports, the null difference between the
experimental and control birth rates does NOT imply that the cap
has had no impact on births to AFDC women.  The correct explanation
for the null difference is that births dropped within both groups
after the new policy took effect.  The family cap, in other words,
has had an even larger and more dramatic impact on births than
expected.[6]</b>
<p>
Explaining the scope of that effect is an exercise in charting
a much broader agenda for political and cultural reform.  While
the family cap is no panacea, it is a critical first step that
logically implies both the destination desired and the reforms
that will be required -- to renew the ethic of individual responsibility
and personal compassion that will restore moral authority to the
Founders' notion of liberty.  The logic of the family cap insists
that relimiting government is itself a moral imperative.
<p>
The most plausible explanation for the success of the New Jersey
cap is that the change in policy sent a clear moral signal that
was at least as important an aspect of the &quot;treatment&quot;
as the restriction on cash benefits.  Dr. Rudy Myers of the New
Jersey Department of Human Services explains:
<p><blockquote>
[T]he treatment in FDP [New Jersey's Family Development Program]
is <I>not </I>a matter of whether or not the AFDC grant is increased
with the birth of the additional child, but is, rather, a matter
of whether or not the individual is exposed to the public publicity
itself -- e.g., newspapers, conversations at the Laundromat, talk
radio, etc.  Suffice it to say that it is extremely implausible
that anyone living in New Jersey for the past several years has
<I>not </I>been exposed to the &quot;family cap&quot; policy.
 &quot;Policy&quot; here cannot be restricted to meaning simply
the law about the family cap; it is the entire line of reasoning
about issues of personal and family responsibility, fairness to
working taxpayers, [and] the rational approach to self-sufficiency.[7]
</blockquote><p>
Because the public discussion of the ideas and values motivating
the law reached women in both the &quot;treatment&quot; and &quot;control&quot;
groups, Dr. Myers concludes that the control group condition cannot
be considered a reasonable proxy for eliminating the effect of
the cap altogether.
<p>
Contrary to liberal rhetoric about the &quot;punitive&quot; nature
of the cap, the success of the New Jersey policy rests on the
power of social persuasion.  The $44 benefit increase eliminated
by the family cap constituted only 4 percent of the total monthly
welfare benefits received by the average AFDC mother in New Jersey.[8]
Those who cry &quot;social engineering&quot; should bear in mind
that the cash limitation itself merely restores government neutrality
after a long interlude of active government favoritism to out-of-wedlock births. 
Women are free to bear as many children as they wish, at their own expense. 
A law with as modest an economic disincentive as the New Jersey
cap almost certainly derives its force from new moral sanctions
against illegitimate childbearing and other personal failings.
<p>
Critics of the cap now question whether a public relations campaign
promoting personal responsibility could be sufficiently forceful
to obviate the need for changes in current welfare policy.  Those
critics forget that laws are indeed moral signaling devices, that
policies cannot belie principles, and that governments cannot
instill a sense of responsibility <I>and </I>provide material
support at the same time.  A public relations campaign is not
sufficient precisely because welfare obviates the need for personal
responsibility and because the &quot;as if&quot; condition, Charles
Murray discovers, does not hold.
<p>
The family cap may be less important than the shift in social
norms that it reflects, but it is a prerequisite for real reform
because it reconciles the current tension between moral knowledge
and the perverse economic incentives of welfare.  The family cap
is an indictment, not of welfare recipients, but of the welfare
system itself.  Illegitimacy, for example, used to be controlled
in large part by the natural economic consequences, until the
economics of welfare intervened to blunt the effect.  Policymakers
will find it impossible to reaffirm a family's ability to meet
their own needs, or even to insist that parenting is a fundamental
and enduring responsibility, without reversing the economic signals
that have sent the opposite message for the last 30 years.  Economic
disincentives to virtue ultimately derange social expectations
so that morality itself no longer has meaning.
<p>
While the family cap will be a necessary first step, by no means
will it prove sufficient to reverse the damage.  Policymakers
should move quickly to terminate cash benefits to unwed minor
mothers and to provide a refundable tax credit to married couples
with children when at least one spouse is employed.  Both policy
recommendations address powerful economic disincentives to marriage
left intact by an exclusive focus on the family cap.  Proactive
measures to encourage family formation, like a tax credit for
adoption expenses, are strongly advisable as well.
<p>
Yet, New Jersey's experiment with the cap demonstrates that the
solution cannot rest entirely with the welfare system or with
new legislation.  Even with the family cap in place, yielding
surprisingly strong results, roughly 10 percent of the state's
unwed welfare mothers continue to bear children each year.[9] If
the family cap derives its power from a larger cultural context,
publicizing the moral reasoning behind the change in law, clearly
all institutions in the community must redouble their efforts
to send strong, unequivocal messages advocating personal and parental
responsibility.
<p>
Perhaps the most compelling argument for the cap is that it is
a symbolic first attempt to begin scaling back the government
programs that have eroded the strength of character-forming institutions
-- the family, the church, the school -- by negating their function.
 An astute Frenchman by the name of Tocqueville identified the
fatal error in policies that seek to take the trouble out of living by 
supplanting voluntary arrangements. &quot;The power of the state,&quot; 
he wrote, &quot;would resemble parental authority if, fatherlike, it tried to 
prepare its charges for a man's life, but on the contrary, it only tries to keep 
them in perpetual childhood.&quot;
<p>
It is time to acknowledge that public policy can undermine, but
never instill, virtue and that restoring the concept of responsibility
implies new obligations, not only for welfare recipients, 
but for members of the middle and upper classes too.  Unless neighbors
are once again moved to trouble over each other, the behavioral
poverty of the underclass will only continue to grow more acute,
jeopardizing personal freedoms and ultimately the survival of
the republic itself.  Children must grow to appreciate what is
great and good in order to make good use of liberty; and even
parents depend on the interplay of thoughtful neighbors to help
pattern right habits of the heart.
<p>
Politicians, for their part, can create the enabling conditions
that foster strong families and communities.  And in addition
to cutting government programs, policymakers should revise the
tax code to encourage charitable giving.  States should also consider
designing executive measures like the Faith and Families program
Governor Fordice has implemented in Mississippi to help speed
the replacement of state solutions by strong civil institutions.[10]
<p>
Ultimately, however, politicians will be dependent on the quiet
saints who man soup kitchens and staff maternity homes to inspire
moral renewal in our land -- to teach man to defend liberty more
for the love of virtue and charity than as a claim of  right or
an end in itself.
<p>
The fate of our experiment with self-government will depend upon
our ability to renew a sense of responsibility across all income
classes, along with a renewed commitment to our Founding Fathers'
faith that all men are created equal to live up to those responsibilities.
<p>
At stake is the future of freedom, but also morality, community,
and family -- all of which depend critically on the preservation
of liberty.  Living in the afterglow of new federal welfare legislation
that has ended the entitlement status of welfare, we would do
well to remember that freedom itself <i>is</i> an entitlement
owed every man by virtue of his birth.
<p>
-- 10/26/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Jennifer E. Marshall is a policy analyst specializing in welfare
reform at the Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based
research and advocacy organization.  This text is adapted from
remarks made by Marshall at an October 1995 Heritage Foundation
forum on welfare reform at the state level.</i>
<p><hr><p>
<h3><center>ENDNOTES</center></h3>
