http://www.conservative.org:80/townhall/FRC/podium/pd95k2lf.html 204.71.237.88 19970209011018 text/html 22524
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 01:11:02 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 14-Mar-96 18:49:19 GMT
Content-length: 22338
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE FAITHFUL</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE<br>
FAITHFUL</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by<br>
Robert G. Morrison</center>
<p>
This speech was the keynote address at the Lutherans for Life
National Convention on November 3, 1995 in Chicago, Illinois.</i>
<p>
People in Washington have particular trouble, it seems, with words
that communicate the things we feel most deeply. We are currently
involved in a great controversy with one of our best friends.
Bill Bennett is a man I've honored and worked for. He has written
letters to Dr. James Dobson and conservative activist Paul Weyrich
taking sharp issue with them over the question of abortion.
<p>
Bennett is a wise man, a man of great learning and experience.
When he speaks, it pays to listen.  In speaking of abortion, Bennett
asks if it would not be better to support a candidate for president
who would actually speak out <I>against</I> abortion, a man who
would support teen abstinence programs that work, a man who would
champion adoption instead of abortion? Wouldn't such a man help
to lower the terrible toll of one and a half million abortions
a year, even if he remained committed to the continuing legality
of abortion? Wouldn't it be better to back someone of high moral
character, Bennett continues, someone who could mount the &quot;bully
pulpit&quot; of the White House in behalf of culturally conservative
ideals?  Isn't such a man <I>preferable </I>to the man who endorses
what Bennett calls the &quot;chimera&quot; of a human life amendment
while providing only &quot;lip service&quot; to the pro-life cause?
<p>
You must give Bill Bennett credit -- he knows how to pose a dilemma.
He's a thoughtful and provocative writer. I hope you will bear
with me if I take some time tonight to respond to the questions
Bennett poses.
<p>
We should welcome this debate. One of the things that has been
so dispiriting about the abortion debate in this country is the
intellectual dishonesty that attends so much of the discussion.
When the election of 1992 finally ended, columnist Charles Krauthammer
wrote that the abortion debate had been decided.
<p>
Many of us cried out that the abortion <I>debate</I> had never
even been held.  Bennett's message is an enticing one. Who among
us is not tired of the trench warfare we have been fighting for
the past 23 years? Isn't it very tempting to break out of the
exhausting and unproductive rut of &quot;politics as usual?&quot;
<p>
Of <I>course,</I> we seek the lowering of the number of abortions.
We know that one and a half million abortions a year is a tragedy.
But are we likely to take the steps necessary to reduce that terrible
toll if we don't think that <I>one</I> abortion is a crime?  What
we see today is the result of a cynicism by public figures. Stalin
said, &quot;A single death is a tragedy, a million deaths is a
statistic.&quot; Too many of our political leaders pay &quot;lip
service&quot; to the tragedy of abortion, but act as if it is
merely another item in the index of leading cultural indicators.
<p>
Of <I>course, </I>we would like to see a president who wholeheartedly
believes that abortion is wrong and who is willing to speak out
against it. A little history will help. America has never had
a president who thought <I>lynching</I> was nice. Most publicly
deplored it. But it was not until President Eisenhower signed
a civil rights law in 1957 that a president acted effectively
to put a stop to lynching. Would lynching have ended sooner if
Eisenhower had supported the choice of legal lynching while using
the White House to speak up for <I>alternatives to lynching</I>?
Ike and Mamie, culturally conservative as they were, could have
been the poster people for opponents of lynching. But it was <I>President
</I>Eisenhower's willingness to use federal marshals and federal
troops that assured the rule of law in such places as Little Rock,
Arkansas.
<p>
Bennett knows philosophy, so he would recognize Thomas Jefferson's
famous taunt. Mr. Jefferson said that if you put a moral question
to a plowman and a philosopher, the plowman would be more likely
to answer rightly. That's because the man who knows little is
closer to the truth than the man who knows many things that aren't
true.
<p>
One of the main things that isn't true is that we pro-lifers would
somehow <I>prefer</I> a president who gives us lip service instead
of solid and constructive action on a life-saving agenda. We were forced 
to <I>accept</I> such weak leadership: we never <I>asked</I> for it. To 
present us only two alternatives -- the pro-abortion president who, 
in his heart, thinks it should be discouraged and is willing to
say so publicly or the insincere pro-life president who pays mere
lip service to a human life amendment -- is to engage in the logical fallacy 
of the &quot;false dilemma.&quot;
<p>
Few people have given so much to our country as Bill Bennett on
a host of issues. When he was interviewed on Dr. James Dobson's
broadcast several years ago, Bennett gave us many wise insights.
On the troubling questions of gays in the military and women in
combat, no one can top Bennett. He told Dr. Dobson's 
listeners that there is a masculine, martial ideal. That ideal
calls upon men, in obedience to lawful authority, to take up arms in defense 
of the weak, the innocent, the vulnerable in order to restore justice
and peace. Bennett gave us an excellent summary of the &quot;just
war&quot; doctrine so wisely taught by Saint Augustine, and so
well elaborated by Martin Luther. Bennett went on: Those who seek
to recruit gays for the military and to place women in combat
seek the destruction of the masculine ideal, the feminine ideal
and the military they have always loathed. No one in American
life has understood these issues better than Bill Bennett, who
never spent a day in the armed forces. No admiral, no four-star
general, <I>not even one particular four-star general,</I> has
understood the challenge so well.
<p>
That is what is so deeply hurtful about the current controversy.
It <I>is </I>a family feud. And <I>you </I>are all part of the
family and you have a right to know what is being argued over.
But it is more than that.
<p>
We thought for a long time we would have to battle for the pro-life
planks in the Republican party platform.  We had no illusions
that the Arlen Specters, Pete Wilsons, Bill Welds and Christine
Todd Whitmans would let this brave statement stand unmolested.
But we never dreamed that we would have to defend the platform
from our friends.
<p>
What <I>does </I>the Republican platform say and why is that important?
Since 1976, the Republicans have been committed to a pro-life
position as a matter of party principle. It is vital that they
remain so. That is because no other major political party in the
world is so committed. Certainly not the conservatives in Britain,
nor the right-wing parties of France, Germany, Canada or Australia.
<p>
The platform adopted in 1984 and secured through 1988 and 1992
said that &quot;the unborn child has a right to life which cannot
be infringed.&quot; It pledged the Republicans to work for a Human
Life Amendment. It further urged the selection of judges at every
level who &quot;respect the sanctity of life and traditional family
values.&quot;
<p>
By saying that he could support a pro-choice president, Bill Bennett
has effectively moved to throw out the 20-year commitment of the
GOP to unborn human life. A platform is a statement the party
makes in advancing its candidates, particularly its presidential
ticket. Bennett has taken up the challenge, saying that we should
not pursue the <I>chimera </I>of a Human Life Amendment.
<p>
This is not the first time he has said this. Several years ago,
in response to a reporter's question on radio station KKLA in
Los Angeles, Bennett said of the pro-life plank that it was OK
with him if they wanted to put that in there. As a practical matter,
he said, it isn't going to happen. So what we should concentrate
on is reducing the numbers.
<p>
Well, as a practical matter, we are not going to get a Human Life
Amendment if our leaders disparage the effort. Scripture tells
us <I>where there is no vision, the people perish. </I>But I think
it a grave mistake to turn from leadership to punditry. We are
every day faced with extraordinary realities which few <I>practical
</I>observers would have predicted.
<p>
Take, for example, the collapse of the Soviet Union. Who, writing
the Republican platform of 1988, would have said the party demands
the reunification of Germany, her inclusion within NATO? Who would
have required the evacuation of all Soviet troops from restored
and sovereign Baltic states before the United States would give
Russia a penny in foreign aid? Anyone writing such a platform
plank in `88 would have been thought mad. But, by 1992, <I>no
platform could even be written </I>which did not take into account
the new <I>practical</I> realities.
<p>
From our own history, we know vast change is possible. In 1860,
the Republicans who met in this city to nominate Abraham Lincoln
and write their platform would not have dared to call for the
abolition of chattel slavery and the extension of U.S. citizenship
to the freedmen. But, <I>by</I> 1864, that change was a <I>practical
</I>reality.
<p>
We do not ask our leaders to do the impossible. We certainly do
not ask them to take us into war. But we do not want them to foreclose
the possibility of great and beneficial change in the <I>practical
</I>realities. 
<p>
The tragedy of Bill Bennett's defection is that it comes at a
time when we can see great and hopeful changes occurring. Naomi
Wolf, a feminist, pro-choice author, has written a remarkable
article in <I>The New Republic.</I> Entitled &quot;Our Bodies,
Our Souls,&quot; Miss Wolf's article is an unusual recognition
of the stakes in this vital question. She writes:
<p>
<blockquote><i>Norma McCorvey explained what happened to her in terms of
good and  evil; she woke in the middle of the night and felt a
presence pushing  violently down on her, &quot;I denounce you,
Satan,&quot; she announced.  This way  of talking about evil is
one of the chief class divisions in America:  working-class people
talk about Satan, and...those who run the country  talk instead
about neurotic guilt. While the elite scoff at research that 
shows most Americans maintain a belief in the embodiment of evil--&quot;the
 devil&quot;--they miss something profound about the human need
to make moral order out of chaos.</i></blockquote>
<p>
Miss Wolf is not an ally. She ends her article where she began
it: staunchly supporting what she calls abortion rights. But the
article is filled with amazing concessions and bold statements.
She dares to tell the truth that every abortion stops a beating
heart. And one word of truth, as Solzhenitsyn says, can move the
world. 
<p>
As if <I>The New Republic's </I>publishing this article were not
amazing enough, it was matched in September by a cover story in
<I>The Atlantic Monthly</I>. George McKenna is a law professor.
He urges pro-life politicians to recognize a woman's constitutional
right to choose abortion, but to take effective, practical measures
to restrict abortion. Ultimately, none of us can accept Professor
McKenna's position, but it is in the <I>laying out </I>of that
position that McKenna does the greatest service to all of us.
For he exposes to the light of day the absurdity underlying the
pro-choice arguments. He links them with the arguments made by
Stephen Douglas' Democrats in the 1850s. How marvelous in our
eyes. <I>Atlantic, </I>a flagship of the liberal prestige press,
has publicly accorded the anti-abortion position the dignity of
the Great Emancipator's cloak. This has not happened before.
<p>
While we are taken up, necessarily and painfully, with the fight
in our own divided house, we should not fail to note that our
adversaries' house is in shambles. Their leader thinks abortion
should be &quot;safe, legal and rare.&quot; If it is a fundamental
constitutional right, as the Supreme Court has told us it is,
then why should it be rare? Is there any other <I>fundamental
</I>human right which any of us would even wish to be rare?
<p>
Lincoln knew all about such hypocrisy. In 1860, he said:
<p>
<blockquote><i>Let us apply a few tests. You say that you think slavery 
is wrong, but you  denounce all attempts to restrain it. Is there
anything else that you think  wrong, that you are not willing
to deal with as a wrong? Why are you so  careful, so tender of
this one wrong and no other? You will not let us <b>do</b> a 
single thing as if it was wrong; there is no place where you will
allow it to  be even <b>called</b> wrong! We must not call it
wrong in the Free States  because it is <b>not</b> there, and
we must not call it wrong in the Slave States  because it is there;
we must not call it wrong in politics because that is  bringing
morality into politics, and we must not call it wrong in the pulpit
because that is bringing politics into religion; we must not
bring it into the  Tract Society or other societies, because those
are such unsuitable places,  and there is no single place, according
to you, where this wrong thing can  properly be called wrong!</i></blockquote>
<p>
Last year, the First Lady told <I>Newsweek</I> interviewers that
abortion was wrong. This was about a week before the mid-term
elections. In September, she went all the way to China to tell
the world that forced abortion is wrong.  One would think from
those statements that the wrong thing would not be included in
her health care plan. We might think that this wrong thing would
not be pressed on every country on earth by means of a diplomatic
cable to every U.S. embassy. We might even hope that this wrong
thing would not be pushed on U.S. military hospitals. Or we might
have thought that abortion would not be part of &quot;coordinated
community services&quot; targeted at public schools in states
which accept funds under federal <I>Goals 2000</I> legislation. From 
all these examples, it appears that their true goal is to make abortion 
safe, legal and <I>well done. </I> But, as Lincoln said, some of us are very
<I>tender</I> and <I>careful </I>about the things we call wrong.
<p>
How much we could have used Bill Bennett's strong voice in pointing
out such lethal inconsistencies. Instead, unfortunately, he has
said that it is Dr. Dobson and Paul Weyrich who are inconsistent.
They are inconsistent, he says, because if they <I>really </I>believe
that human lives are being unjustly taken in abortion, they would
be leading the public effort to put women in jail.
<p>
This is a painful wound, coming from a friend. It speaks volumes
about the circles that Bennett is moving in if he really believes
this. He should know better. Bennett knows American history. He
knows American law. He should know that in all of American history
we have found only <I>two </I>instances of women being prosecuted
for having abortions. The good, protective pro-life laws which
existed in every state until the early sixties, and which saved
the lives of millions of unborn children and their mothers, sought
to punish, discourage and stigmatize the <I>abortionist.</I> That's
the truth, and Bennett should know it. And if he doesn't <I>know
</I>the truth, we would at least appreciate his not taking his
debating points from Planned Parenthood's briefing book.
<p>
Bill Bennett had no greater supporters and enthusiasts than us
when he was taking on the hateful, violent and vulgar products
of gangsta rap. Those who sing about raping women and killing
cops should not be cultural heroes. And those who profit from
this execrable trade should be publicly shamed. And God bless
Bennett for doing it.
<p>
Now he has joined with Sen. Joe Lieberman, Democrat of Connecticut,
to attack daytime TV talk shows. Again, we say, &quot;Good for
you!&quot; Bennett has called the toxic waste spewing forth from
the tube &quot;an affront to human dignity.&quot; How right he
is.
<p>
But, while he has Joe Lieberman's ear, could he put in a word
about <I>another </I>affront to human dignity?  Could he mention
to his friend how helpful his support would be in the fight against
partial birth abortions?  We must understand how inevitable a
degraded and violent culture becomes when we have accepted the
degrading violence of abortion.
<p>
We just won a great victory in the House, as you know. That vote
of 288-139 to ban partial-birth abortions spanned a broad spectrum.
We won the votes of Henry Hyde, Linda Smith and Helen Chenoweth,
to be sure. But we also gained the support of Dick Gephardt, David
Bonior and even young Patrick Kennedy. Bill Bennett should recognize 
that a pro-life commitment <I>can</I> be the source of great
strength. More than that, a pro-life commitment is the <I>only
</I>way a conservative majority can be sustained in this country. As Gary 
Bauer has noted, can Newt Gingrich point to any <I>other </I>bill that gained 
such strong support in the House?
<p>
Many of us, as pro-lifers, are powerfully moved by the fate of
unborn children. We identify strongly with the child in <I>The
Silent Scream.</I> We empathize strongly, and we want to help
defend and preserve the lives that are threatened with abortion.
We believe that God Himself has called us to do this work.
<p>
But there may be more arguments that can be made to the author
of such works as <I>The Book of Virtues </I>and <I>The Moral Compass,
</I>for one of the cardinal virtues that is wisely taught in the
great Catholic tradition is <I>justice. </I>Abortion is not only
violent and bloody. War is that. Abortion is also <I>unjust. </I>And
those who sit on the nation's highest court, who have told us
that the right to abortion is to be found in the &quot;liberty
interest&quot; of our Constitution, are not dispensing justice,
but <I>injustice.</I>
<p>
Lincoln was certainly moved by the fate of the poor slave. He
said that even a dumb brute, <I>even an ant,</I> knows when he
is wronged. But it was this conscious embrace of <I>injustice
</I>which Lincoln likened to a wen, a cancer, a dread disease.
If unchecked, Lincoln knew, it would one day claim the life of
the country itself.
<p>
It is also the federal judiciary which has so consistently undermined
law enforcement in our country. Small wonder, then, that when
justices are indifferent to justice, juries nullify verdicts and
people get away with murder. So, we must tell our neighbors, don't
expect that the blood-rimmed tide will ebb before it gets to <I>your
</I>doorstep. Making abortion legal makes America a violent, bloody
and dangerous place to live. Making abortion legal unravels the
very fabric of society.
<p>
Edmund Burke said we should love our country, that in order to
be loved our country should be lovely. A pro-abortion America
can never be lovely. How can we assert our own right to life if
we, as a nation, deny it to others?
<p>
I wish I could report to you tonight that the fight between Bill
Bennett and the rest of us is just--Washington loves this word--a
flap. I would be happy to say it will soon be smoothed over, and
we will all be friends again. But abortion is not simply an <I>issue</I>,
as Bennett sometimes calls it. It is no more <I>an issue</I> than
Pilate's calling for a choice between Jesus and Barabbas was a
straw poll. To say that we might advance our cause by choosing
leaders who don't understand or believe in our cause is to risk
all that we have accomplished in public policy, all that moves
us to take part in civic life.
<p>
So I am here to report to you that the mood of pro-lifers in Washington
is resolute, unyielding. And I sense that yours is, too. We are
ready to walk with you in the footsteps of the faithful. We will
not break faith with God or with you. If we suffer defections, broken 
friendships, that is regrettable. But that will not deter us.
Churchill, who knew what it was to stand alone, kept faith in
his time with the long history of Christian civilization against
a brutal, pagan tyranny. He would not speak of dark days, but
of <I>stern </I>days. These, too,  are stern days. 
I think we can win the fight for the Republican pro-life platform.
But, no matter what happens, I know that we will never give in.
Thirteen years ago, Jean Garton spoke to a right to life convention
in Connecticut. She spoke memorably then, as she always does.
Her word at that time was <I>reticulation</I>. She described it
as the veins in a leaf. If one was blocked, or cut off, others
could always take its place. So, if we are blocked in the political realm, 
we can still find paths of service. All that is needed is that we continue 
in the footsteps of the faithful. Thank you and God bless you.
<p>
-- 11/13/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Robert G. Morrison is special assistant to the president and
a policy analyst with the Family Research Council, a Washington,
D.C.-based research and advocacy organization.</i>

<p>

