</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>THE CASE FOR REBUILDING CIVIL SOCIETY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>THE CASE FOR REBUILDING<br>
CIVIL SOCIETY</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by<br>
Dr. Michael Novak</i></center>
<p>
<i>This speech was the keynote address at the Family Research
Council's &quot;World Without Welfare&quot; symposium on December
13, 1995 at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C.</i>
<p>
Thank you for allowing me to come to this important conference
and to share in the really central work of the Family Research
Council.
<p>
When we talk about welfare, it's good to make a distinction right
up front.  The war on poverty in the mid-1960s did make a real
difference for the elderly, for the sick, and for the disabled
that we shouldn't disregard.  It was in certain aspects a great
success for the elderly, for example.  In 1965, the largest group
of the poor were those over age 65.  In the 1960s, in John Kennedy's
campaign and when Michael Harrington's book was being bruited
about, pictures of the poor on the covers of <I>Life</I> magazine
or <I>Look</I> or other magazines of the time were inevitably
pictures of the elderly.  If you look today, by almost every measure,
the elderly are almost entirely out of poverty.  If there are
elderly poor, it's because they are not connected to systems that
are in place to help them.  Moreover, in 1965 we counted as elderly
all people who were 65 or over.  Today, the real worrisome part
of the elderly is the &quot;elderly elderly,&quot; the over 85s,
whose numbers have increased to proportions that are comparable
to the proportions of those over 65 just 30 years ago.
<p>
Now the financial aspects of this accomplishment, the funding
mechanisms that we used, are still serious problems.  And thus
we're quite worried about the future of Medicare and even the
future of Social Security.  But the programs in and of themselves
were a great success, and I think it's worth setting that aside
from our discussion for the moment -- although the funding mechanisms
do need a great deal of attention.  It is also true that the position
of the disabled and the sick is much better than it was just 30
years ago.
<p>
<center><h3>THE FAILURE OF AFDC</h3></center>
<p>
There is, nonetheless, a sense in which welfare programs have
dramatically failed.  When we say welfare, we typically mean the
poverty programs that were addressed to young people, young adults
between the ages of 16 and 45 in particular.  And the chief program
that has been worrisome has been AFDC, Aid to Families with Dependent
Children.  In the late 1930s when it was founded, AFDC was predominantly
a program for widows; and for many years afterward, 95 percent
or more of the people who received aid under that program were
widows whose husbands were hurt in mining accidents or mill accidents
or some other kind of accident.  Then after 1965, with great rapidity,
AFDC became a program predominantly for young single women having
children out of wedlock.  When we say welfare in America, when
the public hears that word, that's the part of the problem they
almost always fix on.  And it is very well worth fixing on.
<p>
The Family Research Council is one of the organizations that grew
up to respond to the insight that, if you help the family -- often,
I should add, unformed families not based on marriage -- you have
identified the surest and most direct safeguard against poverty.
If the family is healthy and functioning well, you don't need
what used to be called the Department of Health, Education and
Welfare.  That's what the family does when it's functioning well.
And when the family isn't functioning well, not everything that
all the Departments of Health, Education and Welfare do can make
up for the loss.  As I once put it, the family is the only Department
of Health, Education and Welfare that works.
<p>
Now, one of the insights that the public senses, but many critics
of welfare reform don't seem to grasp, is the sheer devastation
wrought by the programs we launched in 1965.  Those of us who
supported the War on Poverty, as I certainly did, did not warn
the citizenry that if you adopt this program we will bring you
a 600 percent increase in violent crime and a 500 percent increase
in births out of wedlock.  That wasn't our intention.  Nobody
foresaw that happening or wanted it to happen.  But that's what
did happen.  In other words, it's important to grasp the damage
that welfare is doing.  The reason for being concerned about welfare
reform today -- and trying to imagine a &quot;world without welfare&quot;
-- is not a budgetary reason.  It's not its cost.  The cost is
not insuperable.  If welfare were doing good, we would gladly
support it.  Most of us would.  I think the vast majority would.
What's disconcerting to people is that welfare is manifestly
doing harm.  Or, to put it another way, it's not achieving the
goods it set out to achieve.  And the problems it set out to address
are not getting better.
<p>
Witness John Kennedy's statement in early 1963 about the first
move toward welfare reform, which later became the War on Poverty
after his death.  The message he sent to Congress said it was
intended to strengthen the American family, to put an end to juvenile
delinquency.  Can you imagine how quaint a term that later would
become?  Who speaks of &quot;juvenile delinquency&quot;?  That's
a term from the 1950s and 1960s.  That's long gone.  It's violent
crime.  Juvenile delinquency was ended.  It became violent crime.
But those were the intentions of the program, and it failed to
achieve them.
<p>
I want to warn you to be careful here too.  It's very hard to
show that welfare has caused all the civic destruction that has
happened since 1965 among families we intended to help.  So many
other things happened, television and affluence and urban renewal.
It's hard to isolate any one explanation.  But at a minimum,
one can say that welfare in this narrower sense that I'm using
was aimed to address these problems and didn't succeed.  The problems
have grown worse than they were 30 years ago.
<p>
<center><h3>HALVING THE FAMILY</h3></center>
<p>
In Washington, D.C., where we are meeting, 64 percent of all pregnancies
end in abortion.  Of those young children who survive that, 70
percent plus are born out-of-wedlock.  Now the fact that they're
born out-of-wedlock means in reality that these youngsters will
be born without the presence of half of an extended family.  That
is, they will generally lack grandparents, uncles, and aunts on
one side of the family.  And on the woman's side of the family,
perhaps the family will be supportive.  Usually it is, but it
may not be.  But already the child's world is cut in half from
what a child would normally have.  And if the child is born into
a household which is disconnected from the world of work and disconnected
from neighbors who also work, that child is born without connections
to the world of work.  The prognosis for later employment is very
poor.  The health prognosis is poor.  The prognosis for finishing
school is poor.  The prognosis for involvement in the criminal
justice system is very high.  In this city, the chances of involvement
in the criminal justice system by the age of 30 are about 80 percent.
So those who want to continue welfare as we know it carry on
their shoulders a very heavy burden of proof.  I believe that
the Catholic bishops who are resisting some of the move for reform
are not facing as directly as they ought the moral responsibility
that accrues to them for continuing the program as it now is.
<p>
One of the worst features of the welfare program as it now is,
especially for the young, is that it takes good healthy young
people who are able to be creative and energetic and to show initiative
and it leaves them in a state of dependency in two respects. 
First, many of them are not there to be able to take care of their
children or their parents.  In other words, the healthy young
adults are usually the ones on whom the elderly depend, not on
whom children depend.  And for the most part, because they are
not working, they do not have the means to take care of those
who depend on them.  But secondly, this seems to bring with it
certain psychic wounds because many such people are not able to
be independent themselves.  They throw themselves on the care
of the government, on the care of the larger society, both for
the care of their dependents and for their own care.  And then
there's a third sense of dependency, too, for a very high proportion
of them.  While their schooling is free, they don't complete school.
Many become involved in alcohol or drugs and in other sorts of
behavior that are self-destructive. 
<p>
In all three of these senses, we have learned since 1965 that
poverty -- that is, a lack of material resources -- is not the
worst consequence but dependency in these three senses is much
worse.  It takes someone who ought to be a self-governing citizen,
self-reliant, brave, showing initiative, creating jobs, and leaves
them in the state of counting on others for the most basic things.
I hate even to bring up this aspect, but generally it leaves
them also with a great loss of spiritual morale, or self-esteem.
It's the self-esteem I hate to mention.  But it is in these cases
a very important reality with which to cope.  It's hard, when
you're not achieving, to have a sense of proper adult achievement.
<p>
America was never founded to be a society for dependent people.
The American experiment is an experiment in self-government,
and I want to talk about that in the second part of my remarks
now.  What it means to have republican government is to have a
government which allows most decisions, most social activities,
to be undertaken by the citizens themselves.  They're self-governing.
They are able to manage their social lives.  They are able to
manage their social necessities.  One of the most extraordinary
things about the founding of this republic, commented on by Tocqueville
50 years after the founding, is the capacity of Americans to organize
themselves to take care of their own needs.
<p>
<center><h3>ASSOCIATION: THE AMERICAN CHARACTER</h3></center>
<p>
My wife and I recovered the diary of an ancestor of hers.  Believe
it or not, his name was Charlie Brown.  He was the son of the
first Baptist missionary in the Iowa Territory before it became
a state, and Charles Brown writes in his diary day after day about
the importance of individualism, the importance of the individual.
But that's not what he describes.  What's in his head is how
much individual initiative it took to depart from the family back
east near Syracuse, and before that in Massachusetts, and to move
out to this new territory where the plow had not cut the soil
ever.  When he arrived, it was buffalo grass.  Not many people
lived there because the native Americans used it mostly as a hunting
ground.  It was not for farming, and most people passed on through.
Day after day, what Brown describes is like &quot;yesterday we
worked on the farm of so and so putting up a barn.&quot;  And
on another day they're putting a bridge over a creek.  And on
another day they're putting up the equivalent of a city hall.
And on another day they're working on the school.  The substance
of his days is working together with neighbors on projects to
make their common life go, to make it work.
<p>
What I'm trying to establish is that this is the building of civil
society.  This is the building of the ability of human beings
to live together in a good community when there's no government,
or only a very diminished form of government.  As Tocqueville
says, this is the great advantage the Americans had.  They were
so lightly governed.  The King and Parliament hardly paid them
attention, except to tax them.  They were organized first in villages
and townships and only much later in counties and states.  Only
after virtually 200 years were they organized in a federal government.
So, Americans learned how to conduct a social life for themselves
before they had government.
<p>
Tocqueville also remarks, in his reflections on the revolution
in France, that at the time of the revolution there were not 10
men in all of France who were capable of practicing the art of
association as Americans were.  What he meant by that was that
in France when something is needed people turn to the state to
do it.  And in Britain people turn to the aristocracy to fund
it. In America, they turned to one another.  They formed associations.
<p>
Tocqueville formed the principle that the first law of democracy
is the principle of association.  The very first law is that democracy
will only work where people are capable of self-government --
forming their own associations and making communal decisions,
and figuring out the mechanisms to make those fairly and well.
Tocqueville observed that people became practiced in the art
of association almost universally in America.  People formed associations,
he observed, to fund missionaries, to build colleges, to put up
buildings, to bring music to a village or town, to stage a play.
They formed associations for every imaginable purpose.  They
didn't turn to government because in the early days there was
no government to turn to, only a government of very limited resources
and very limited authority.
<p>
Now this is what our Framers intended by the experiment in self-government,
&quot;of the people, by the people, for the people.&quot;  For
this reason, governments are formed among men to secure these
rights. You do have to have a government, as the generation of
our Framers discovered for themselves when they were badly governed
by the Articles of Confederation.  They needed to form a more
perfect Constitution to form a more perfect union.  Their project
was not an anti-government program, in other words.  But it was
a matter of getting government right, and part of getting government
right was to leave space for people to govern themselves.  So
&quot;government by government&quot; would play as small a role
as necessary.  That is the original and has been the continuing
American experiment, and I think that the restlessness we are
seeing in the country is an urge to return to something like that
-- to &quot;devolve,&quot; as current rhetoric would have it.
Largely because of the great wars of the 20th century, the first
world war and the second, the federal government has far more
centralized power than anyone had earlier envisaged.
<p>
<center><h3>ESCAPING POVERTY THE FAMILY WAY</h3></center>
<p>
It isn't fair to say that all of our associations or social units
are voluntary.   Most are, but there are some that are given to
us by nature.  And one of those is the family.  I've already mentioned
the centrality of the family, but let me give you one more little
factoid that's impressive.  If you do three things in the United
States, it's very difficult to be poor -- less than a five percent
chance.  The first is to complete high school, which is free and
in fact mandatory.  In most states you can be picked up by a truant
officer for not attending school, but a substantial number of
people still don't.  Secondly, you are likely to avoid poverty
if you work full-time, even at a minimum wage job.   And finally,
you should get married or, with difficulty, manage to stay married.
<p>
Just a very few years ago, only about 6 percent of married couple
families were poor.  Today it's about 8 percent.  Marriage alone,
then, gives you a 92 percent chance of getting out of poverty.
The two incomes, in any case the support of two people, seem
to have some financial and also psychological power that is of
great assistance.  And, of course, with work and with at least
the minimum of a high school education, you do very well.  We
see this being realized every day.
<p>
One of the things that has changed the argument in the country
dramatically in the last 20 years is the influx of immigrants
from very poor backgrounds from all over the world.  They arrive
financially poor, but in a short time are <I>not</I> poor.  Their
success through family and work -- and particularly their success
in pushing their children in education -- has led them to move
out of poverty.  That in turn has restored our faith in the possibilities
within the American system for helping the poor regularly move
out of poverty.  What sticks in the craw of Americans, in fact,
is the vision before their eyes of so many people not moving out
of poverty.  That's what's uncharacteristic, that's what's unprecedented.
And that's what gives people the sense that the system is failing.
The system is meant to move people out of poverty within a decade
or so, a generation at most.  And when it's not doing that, that's
what makes people say there is something wrong with the system,
something we've done wrong in our design of it.
<p>
It's always wise to remind yourself that the vast majority of
people who are poor and who are on welfare are white.  The press
often tries to portray this as a &quot;black problem&quot; --
that is, they will frequently show black people when they talk
about welfare.  But any of you who come from states with more
rural settings, or states with smaller towns and cities, know
the increase in welfare among whites all over the United States.
Even the increase of illegitimacy today among whites is now higher
than it was in 1965 when Daniel Patrick Moynihan declared it a
disaster among blacks.  It's now higher among whites and growing
more rapidly than among blacks.
<p>
The family, therefore, is one of the crucial places to apply our
attention.  This is not habitual among social scientists and American
intellectuals in general.  Political thought for the last 200
years has been more or less mesmerized by the two great discoveries
of the last 200 years: the nation-state and the individual.  For
the first time in history, a great many individuals moved away
from their families through migration or through the opening up
of new occupations.  They moved into occupations untraditional
in their family.  Sometimes they changed their religious background.
It's been a hugely migratory two centuries.  All of us here are
a part of that migration to the United States over a very short
period, the greatest migration in human history. We became aware,
therefore, of separating from family, of being an individual.
And there are many other factors that led to this as well.  
<p>
<center><h3>&QUOT;THE GREAT DRAMATIC MIDDLE&QUOT;</h3></center>
<p>
But simultaneously, we became aware of the formation of the nation-state.
And thus by and large progressives -- liberals as we tend to
call them in this country -- when presented with a problem, typically
tend to think of a state solution for it.  And on the other hand,
conservatives faced with a problem typically have tried to think
of something that the individual could do.  And our social thought
has been oscillating between these two extreme views: the individual
and the state.  We have overlooked the great dramatic middle in
which most human life is lived.
<p>
I don't know about you, but practically the only place I get to
be alone is on an airplane.  And I get to be alone only after
I answer two questions.  The person next to me always eventually
says, &quot;What do you do?&quot;  And I figured out the answer
that stops most of them cold.  I say, &quot;I teach,&quot; in
roughly that tone of voice.  Most of them have dreadful memories
of school, and that usually ends the conversation right there.
A few of them are brave souls and they will say, showing their
sophistication, &quot;What do you teach?&quot;  And I have a perfect
answer for that too.  I say, in as brief a voice as I can, &quot;Humanities.&quot;
And they say, &quot;Oh.&quot;  And that's it, I'm free.  There
are no committee meetings and no telephones.  For an hour and
a half or four hours, or whatever it is, I have the first solitude
I've had in days.  The rest of the time seems to be spent in committees
and meetings.  Most of our time is spent with other people.
<p>
American life is probably the most social life in the world. 
One of the most difficult tasks in America is getting the whole
family to sit down together at the dinner table because somebody
always has band practice or hockey practice, or a meeting.  And
if you want to get one night together, you almost have to enforce
it the way the Mormons do.   It has to be a family night, and
everybody must be home.  I had an Italian friend, and I asked
him why he came to work in &quot;Cleave-a-land,&quot; which is
how he said it. &quot;To make money, to find fortune,&quot; he
said.  &quot;And why did you go back to Italy?&quot; I asked.
&quot;To live,&quot; he said.  In Italy you take a shave and
a haircut -- two hours.  In America, eight minutes.  In Italy
you have dinner all evening -- four hours, normal.  In America,
in the evenings you're at meetings.  He said the trouble with
America is that you work eight hours a day and then you go to
eight hours of meetings.  We're a very social people, with our
families and all the different organizations and groups that we
belong to.  We live a richly social life.
<p>
It's not a community life in the way the Europeans imagined community,
however.  When the Europeans imagine community they always think
of a village somewhere in the mountains where everybody shares
the same faith and the same outlook and families have known one
another for hundreds of years and are almost like family together.
That's the European sense of community.  It is not, I think,
the highest sense of community.  It's a lovely form of community,
but it is quite oppressive and often xenophobic.  It distresses
others, and it is often repressive of the talents and abilities
of rare people within it.
<p>
Well, to pick up the theme I began with, the family, the association,
the capacity of Americans to look around, see a need and form
an organization to meet it -- that is what a &quot;world without
welfare&quot; is going to call on Americans to do more and more.
My friend Phil Merrill, who is the publisher of the <I>Washingtonian</I>
and other newspapers in this city and a shrewd observer of life,
predicts that in the next 20 years there's going to be the most
massive transfer of wealth in the history of this republic.  He
points out, &quot;Just look at pictures of the city of Washington
30 years ago and overlay them with a photograph of today.  Look
at how many new buildings have gone up.  Look at areas like Bethesda
and Falls Church and the whole surrounding area that were residential
communities and today are bustling communities with factories
and offices of every sort all over.  Think of the fortunes that
have been made in auto dealerships and real estate.&quot;  People
have more money than they are going to be able to leave to their
children.  Most of that money will go into the greatest outbreak
of philanthropy that the country has ever known, and therefore
that the world has ever known.
<p>
The stock market, in the 12 months of this year, has gone up one
trillion dollars of new wealth.  It's just astonishing what is
going on around us.  New industries, new technologies that were
not even thought of, are coming on-line.  When people talk about
our children being worse off than we were when we grew up and
lacking the same opportunities, they are overlooking the wealth
in home ownership and pensions -- the hidden forms of wealth that
are not usually counted.  When you see these comparisons of the
concentration of wealth, they almost all leave out your home,
your personal possessions, your compact discs.  What most of us
count as our wealth isn't counted.  What they count as wealth
is stock ownership, which some 20 to 30 million American families
have, but not everybody.  Thus, those studies have a necessary
conclusion that wealth is concentrated because they count only
a certain kind of wealth.
<p>
<center><h3>CATS, CHOICES, AND CHARACTER</h3></center>
<p>
Now, the last requirement of a self-governing society -- beyond
the capacity to form associations, to strengthen families, and
to form associations to meet whatever needs we discern -- is the
personal requirement.  The project of self-government will only
succeed with a certain kind of people.  It's a fantasy, Madison
said, to imagine that a republic can be made to work without virtue.
Now by the word &quot;virtue,&quot; the Framers meant certain
habits that a people must have if it wishes to be a free people.
They thought that there are peoples on this planet who are not
capable of liberty because they do not have the habits of self-government.
And they, therefore, will not be able to make self-government
work.  Now what did they mean by &quot;self-government&quot;?
They meant the capacity for two actions in particular.  Out of
all the things human beings do, there are two that are most particular
to our being human.  One is the capacity for reflection or deliberation.
And the other is the capacity for choosing.  And the two together
are what make liberty.
<p>
The capacity for deliberation or for reflection is a simple one.
I can best explain it in relationship to the two cats we have
at home.  I hate cats, you have to understand.  But our daughters
when they were 6 and 7 years old, each brought home a cat and
begged us to adopt them, lest they meet a terrible fate.  They
promised they would take care of the cats forever, and the parents
would never have to do anything.  The only problem is our children
are grown up and gone, and we still have the cats.  We can't even
leave home without finding a catsitter.  One is orange, and one
is black and white.  One is thin, and one is fat.  And one is
quick, and one is slow and dimwitted.  There's no question that
our cats have different personalities.
<p>
On the other hand, there's one thing we never have to worry about,
as we do have to worry with our children -- What career are they
going to choose?  Our children act.  They think of things that
we wish they wouldn't think of and then do them.  Our cats, on
the other hand, behave as cats always have since the time the
first one posed for the Sphinx.  In 5,000 years, cats have done
nothing original.  It's behavior.  Our children are capable of
reflecting on the future, seeing alternatives and choosing among
them.  They're capable of looking back on the past and finding
things that they're sorry for and things they're pleased with
and happy about.  That capacity to reflect is crucial to liberty.
<p>
Our Framers distinguished between two different kinds of liberty.
Tocqueville points this out in the first pages of <I>Democracy
in America</I>: the liberty proper to animals and the liberty
proper to human beings.  Our cats just do what they please.  Whatever
instinct tells them to do, they do.  They cannot do other than
obey their instincts.  Human beings have several different sets
of instincts which are at war with one another.  And human beings
have to choose which instincts to follow.  The capacity for self-government
is the capacity to choose under the light of reflection and deliberation.
The French built the Statue of Liberty to reflect this new idea
of liberty.  The idea of &quot;libert&eacute;&quot; failed in
the French Revolution, but the idea of liberty succeeded in North
America -- the kind of liberty that Pope John Paul II has insisted
on calling Ordered Liberty ever since his first visit to America.
That, he said, is the great contribution of American civilization
to world civilization.  The concept of the practice and institutions
of ordered liberty.
<p>
The French didn't know what sort of monument to build.  They wanted
to build one of the great monuments of the world.  They formed
a committee.  Being French, their first decision was easy.  It
would be the figure of a woman.  A woman is the symbol of liberty
in French oceanography from at least the fifth century.  Not the
young male with a weapon, but a woman, Lady Wisdom.  In her right
arm, they put the torch of reason, of light against the mist and
fog of bigotry and passion and ignorance.  And in her other arm
they put the book of the law.  Liberty under reason, liberty under
law.  It's a distinctive understanding of liberty.  To be free
is to act from reflection and deliberation, which is hard.  Often
we act out of instinct, out of passion, out of impulse.  But to
act soberly with reflection and self-mastery, as Jefferson and
Washington are described, is the very model of self-government.
Now how, Madison asked, can you have self-government in the republic
if you don't have self-government in the citizens?  You can't
imagine that a people incapable of self-government in their private
lives can practice self-government in their public lives.
<p>
Now I think what we need to understand is that this is our model
for the poor.  It always has been -- just as it has been for the
rich.  The capacity for self-government, the capacity for a certain
independence, for reflective and deliberate behavior, and the
acceptance of the consequences of decisions.  And that's exactly
what our current welfare programs have destroyed in large numbers
of people.  And poor people coming from around the world see this
and tell themselves, &quot;Stay off welfare.  It's a honey trap.
It can so easily destroy.&quot;
<p>
<center><h3>TOWARD A &QUOT;WORLD WITHOUT WELFARE&QUOT;</h3></center>
<p>
Well, when we talk about reconstituting civil society, that's
our agenda.  It's an agenda on a very full spectrum.  Everything
from recovering the habits that Bill Bennett tried to bring to
our attention in the <I>Book of Virtues</I>, to renewing the spirit
of volunteerism, the habit of Americans to look around and see
what needs doing, and then do it themselves without turning to
government.  If we have government help, then we will often need
to find ways of having the government help indirectly rather than
directly.  Rather than giving direct subsidies, we should find
an indirect way of helping institutions that encourage the independent,
self-reliant, community-minded behavior that is proper to self-government.
We need a whole new imagination about what we're going to ask
of government and how we're going to ask it to help.
<p>
We know that in a society as mobile and intercontinental as we
are, there are going to be people who fall through the net.  Families
aren't going to be there to help them because they're far from
their families.  In this sense, we understand that there has to
be a welfare net of some kind.  But how to provide this help?
It does not have to be done in the manner in which it has been
done for the last 30 years.  We've succeeded for the elderly,
but it was a grand failure for young people despite all good intentions.
So our agenda is a very large one, and it's useful as we begin
these reflections for the day to keep in mind how many different
things we have to do at once.  It's an entire rethinking, reformulating
or reconstituting, of the American experiment -- something that
Jefferson said that we ought to do every 18 and a third years
just on principle.  Thank you very much.
<p>
-- 2/1/96
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Dr. Michael Novak is the George Frederick Jewett Chair in Religion
and Public Policy at the American Enterprise Institute in Washington,
D.C.</i>

