<title>RECLAIMING THE FAMILY: WHAT PETER UHLENBERG CAN TEACH US</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">

<h2>RECLAIMING THE FAMILY:<br>
WHAT PETER UHLENBERG CAN TEACH US</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by<br>
William R. Mattox, Jr.</i></center>

<p>

<i>This speech was presented at the James Madison Institute's
&quot;Reclaiming America's Cultural and Moral Heritage&quot; conference
on April 20, 1996 in Clearwater, Fla.</i>

<p>

One of the first questions that nearly every public opinion pollster
in Washington asks survey respondents is, &quot;Do you think the
country is generally on the right track or on the wrong track?&quot;
Answers to this question typically offer a crude indication of
the public's mood at any given point in time and a useful measurement
for monitoring shifts in attitudes over time.

<p>

For many years, there was a strong correlation between people's
perceptions about the country's direction and the health of the
U.S. economy.  When the economy was up, people thought America
was on the right track.  When the economy was down, Americans
perceived that we were off course as a nation.  In fact, so closely
did these two measurements track together that if there were a
significant change-up or down-in the index of leading economic
indicators, pollsters could reliably predict that a corresponding
shift in the mood of the country would begin showing up about
six months later.  It was all very predictable.

<p>

But several years ago, something dramatic happened.  As America
began to pull out of the recession that hit in the early 1990s,
the public mood did not shift significantly.  It remained in the
doldrums.  While the country experienced improving economic conditions,
roughly two in three Americans continued to maintain that the
country was on the &quot;wrong track.&quot;  Understandably, this
caught many pollsters off guard.  They began to ask follow up
questions to see why so many Americans were pessimistic about
America's future.

<p>

What they found was quite interesting.  While some pessimists
cited downsizing or joblessness or other sorts of economic concerns,
most identified cultural concerns as the primary reason for their
pessimism.  Indeed, several recent polls have shown that as many
as four out of five Americans believe that it is significantly
tougher for a kid to grow up in America today than it was a generation
or two ago.

<p>

If we were to transport ourselves back in time, I suspect the
situation we now find ourselves in would surprise many Americans.
Imagine, for a moment, a scene from, say, 30 or 35 years ago.
A pollster knocks on the door of a young couple and says, &quot;Three
decades from now, there will be no more Soviet Union.  There will
be no more Berlin Wall.  There will be no more Cold War.  America
will be the world's only military superpower.  It will have a
Gross National Product at least three times its current size.
Given these conditions, do you believe America will be or will
not be on the right path?&quot;

<p>

I suspect many at that time would have answered affirmatively,
imagining that America had entered a glorious age.  Yet, if you
ask the American people today, they'll tell you something very
different.  They will tell you that while living standards may
be increasing in America, the quality of life is declining.  And
lest one attribute such downbeat conclusions to Americans' unrealistic
expectations, it bears mentioning that schoolchildren today do
not crawl under their desks to participate in some sort of a mock
nuclear attack drill -- in some schools, students crawl under
their desks to escape real bullets shot in one direction or another
by one of their peers.

<p>

In thinking about cultural decline and some of the problems that
have arisen in the last 35 years, I think there are at least three
lessons to be learned from the work of a sociologist at the University
of North Carolina named Peter Uhlenberg.   While I recognize that
his work may be unfamiliar to many of you, it should be noted
that long before Dan Quayle ever took on <I>Murphy Brown</I>,
or Bill Bennett ever introduced his <I>Index of Leading Cultural
Indicators</I>, or Hillary Clinton ever penned <I>It Takes a Village
to Raise a Child</I>, Peter Uhlenberg was addressing many of the
questions we are wrestling with today in the public arena.

<p>

Indeed, 10 years ago in 1986, Uhlenberg and one of his colleagues
wrote an essay that appeared in Irving Kristol's <I>Public Interest</I>
called, &quot;The Declining Well-Being of America's Youth.&quot;
The article began by arguing that the 1960s and the 1970s should
have been a golden age for young people if you look simply at
the factors social scientists say are most critical to healthy
child development.  During this time period, median family income
rose, average family size declined, and the educational background
of parents increased.  Moreover, Uhlenberg reported that the 1960s
and the 1970s were a time when there was a great deal of government
spending on programs directed toward children, most especially
public education.

<p>

Yet, at the end of this 20 year period, children's lives had not
improved dramatically.  Quite the opposite.  Citing a litany of
statistical indicators that would later make their way into Bill
Bennett's index, Uhlenberg showed that virtually every common
measurement -- teen pregnancy, juvenile crime, school test scores,
and the rest -- showed a decline in the well-being of America's
youth.

<p>

In reporting these (surprising) results, Uhlenberg challenged
social scientists -- and the public policymakers who feed off
of their work -- to consider the limits and the inevitable shortcomings
of their work.  He wrote:

<p><blockquote>

<i>Could it be that social scientists have overlooked the most crucial
determinants of children's welfare?  Could a preoccupation with
variables that are amenable to empirical measurement or to public
policy manipulation have diverted attention from variables that
are more important?</i>

</blockquote><p>

If, according to Uhlenberg, most of the scientific and policy
elite were barking up the wrong tree, what did he and his colleague
believe was responsible for the decline in children's well being
during the 1960s and 70s? Interestingly, Uhlenberg attributed
this decline to a decrease in &quot;sacrificial love.&quot;  Now,
he didn't use those words exactly.  No self-respecting social
scientist would ever use the &quot;L&quot;-word in a scholarly
journal, even one as unprententious as <I>The Public Interest</I>.
But make no mistake -- that is precisely what Uhlenberg was talking
about.  In fact, he said that while there had been a significant
increase in public investments in children, there had been a corresponding
decrease in private investments in children.  Most notably, there
had been a significant decline in the number of children that
were being raised in broken homes and a decline as well in the
amount of time two-earner families were spending with their children.

<p>

All of this gave Uhlenberg reason to believe that there were more
kids growing up without the &quot;one key ingredient&quot; that
Cornell psychologist Urie Brofenbrenner has called essential to
successful child development -- that &quot;someone has to be crazy
about the kid.&quot;

<p>

Now Uhlenberg admitted, of course, that &quot;craziness&quot;
about children is something very difficult for social scientists
to measure.  He wrote:

<p><blockquote>

<i>It is very difficult to define and even more difficult to measure
the quality of relationships.  It is even more difficult to design
policies for improving the relationships between individuals in
an intimate environment.  By contrast, measures of income, or
inequality, or family size or school expenditures are rather straightforward,
and policies designed to transfer more goods and services to children
can be conducted with relative ease.  But if the problems of American
youth stem from the state of parent-child relationships, those
who propose to improve the situation by designing policies which
bypass the family are embarking on a futile quest.  Perhaps we
are faced with a situation in which there is no change in public
policy that can have much effect or at least it seems that the
changes needed lie in an entirely different direction than those
generally advocated.</i>

</blockquote><p>

The first lesson, then, that we can derive from Peter Uhlenberg's
work is that we need to appreciate the limits of social science
and the limits of public policy.  Certainly this is a lesson for
liberals  in our day who have, over the course of the last several
decades, put a great deal of hope in government programs.  Not
only have these programs often failed to meet the high-minded,
well-intentioned goals of their sponsors, but they have in many
cases had all sorts of unintended consequences that have made
matters worse.  As Charles Murray has noted, the classic example
of the Law of Unintended Consequences is the modern welfare state,
and specifically the provision of cash entitlements to women who
bear children out of wedlock.  While such programs were intended
to help single mothers deal with a very difficult situation, they
have actually had the effect of encouraging greater illegitimacy
while discouraging the very behaviors likely to help one avoid
or overcome poverty.

<p>

Clearly, for those of us who see the folly of big government and
who want to see the well-being of children improve, there is much
work to be done in the public policy arena.  We need to be about
the business of clearing the underbrush of government programs
that are choking the health of our society and exacerbating many
of the social problems entrenched especially in the inner city.
We need to offer tax relief for families with children to make
it easier for parents to invest time in their children.  We need
to  pass divorce reform legislation that makes it considerably
more difficult (if not impossible) for individuals to walk away
from their marital commitments unilaterally.  We need to pass
school choice measures that make it easier for parents to be involved
in the most important decisions surrounding their children's education.

<p>

In addition to the conventional, pro-family policy agenda, we
need to consider other issues that affect the well-being of America's
children.  For example, I would like to see an investigation into
the role of old-age entitlements and the degree to which many
well-intentioned programs diminish bonds between generations.
I'd also like to see an exploration of zoning ordinances, and
the degree to which they contribute to the fact that many Americans
live in cookie-cutter enclaves with people whose social class,
race, age, and income are very much like their own.

<p>

Having said that, there is reason for liberals to take note of
Uhlenberg's observations about the limits of public policy (and
having argued for a conservative counter-revolution to free Americans
from the influence of big government), I think it is important
to encourage conservatives to heed Uhlenberg's cautions about
the limits of public policy as well.  Conservatives -- most especially,
religious conservatives -- should be careful not to place too
much hope in a political revolution. Yes, a conservative revolution
can bring about pro-family tax relief -- but it cannot guarantee
that parents will spend the extra discretionary time tax cuts
buy investing in their children.  Yes, conservative revolutionaries
can straighten out divorce laws -- but no law can make a man love
his wife in the way that he ought.  Yes, conservative revolutionaries
can give parents school choice -- but choice alone cannot guarantee
the kind of parental involvement that is so critical to student
achievement.

<p>

Now my point is not to suggest that public policy does not matter.
Obviously, it matters a great deal.  My point instead is simply
to suggest that a conservative revolution cannot produce the shining
city on a hill that Margaret Thatcher referred to last night.
I think we need to be reminded of this particularly since this
is an election year, when many Americans, to one degree or another,
imagine some sort of political knight in shining armor riding
in to make everything right with the world.  Surely, the outcome
of elections is critically important, but it is a mistake to put
our hope in a political savior.   As Peter Uhlenberg's work reminds
us, we must appreciate both the benefits and the limits of science
and government.  We must not look to either to save us.

<p>

The second lesson we need to learn from Dr. Uhlenberg's work may
surprise you.  In a 1986 speech he gave amplifying some of the
themes that he had originally laid out in the <I>Public Interest</I>
article, Uhlenberg said it takes a whole village to raise a child.
Now, those weren't his exact words.  And he had something very
different in mind than some who have picked up on this theme in
recent months.  But Uhlenberg makes an interesting -- and much
needed -- point.  Here's what he says:

<p><blockquote>

<i>The isolated nuclear family tends to be a fragile and vulnerable
organization.  Critics of the nuclear family are correct in asserting
that it is unreasonable to expect a husband and wife to meet all
of the social, economic, and emotional needs of each other and
of their children, especially in times of crisis.</i>

</blockquote><p>

He goes on later in his speech to say:

<p><blockquote>

<i>Families are not designed to stand in isolation but rather should
be enmeshed in strong webs of other supportive relationships.
The caring and rearing of children is certainly the responsibility
of parents, and the burdens and the joys of child rearing should
be shared with persons outside of the nuclear family.</i>

</blockquote><p>

Lest one interpret this as a call for government activism to support
families, Uhlenberg is quick to point out that he has something
very different in mind.  He said, &quot;Rather than concluding
that families should be bypassed and that government bureaucracies
relied upon to meet these needs, families could be encouraged
to join together in supportive networks.&quot;

<p>

I hadn't really given a great deal of thought to Uhlenberg's observations
about the importance of supportive networks until two years ago
when a not-so-random-act-of-kindness by a woman named Betty Rudisill
left me speechless.

<p>

Betty Rudisill is a woman who lives in the &quot;village&quot;
where I was raised.  A long-time family friend and one-time neighbor,
Mrs. Rudisill is best remembered by me as the woman who used to
save all her junk mail so that I could put it in my &quot;business
box&quot; and pretend to be a businessman.  (Some would say that
I am still pretending.)

<p>

Mrs. Rudisill is one of the first people my mother turned to when
she needed help of some kind with her kids.  Indeed, it was at
Mrs. Rudisill's house one day after school that I received a jubilant
phone call from my father at the hospital maternity ward telling
me that I had a new kid brother.

<p>

Well, I haven't seen Betty Rudisill in probably 10 years.  But
a couple of years ago, she learned that my two oldest kids were
in town visiting their grandparents.  So, she invited my mother
to bring the kids over to her house for a little tea party.  Mrs.
Rudisill then proceeded to offer these two kids she had never
even met before one of the most enchanting afternoons of their
young lives.  Mrs. Rudisill introduced my daughter to an elaborate
collection of delicate dolls with which her daughter had once
played.  And she gave my boy an opportunity to thoroughly check
out the collection of Matchbox cars that had once delighted her
son.  Needless to say, it was quite a party.  And it made quite
an impression on my children.

<p>

Now, I don't want to get carried away here.  I don't want to exaggerate
the importance of this episode.  In the end, Mrs. Rudisill's tea
party is not apt to rank as one of the most important events in
my children's lives.  Times spent with family members like Mom
and Dad and Grandmother and Papa are likely to be far more important.

<p>

But it is also true that my children's lives are richer because
of Mrs. Rudisill's kindness.  Indeed, episodes like this serve
to reinforce what my wife and I try to teach our children with
our words and actions -- that they are more of a delight than
a bother, that they are important human beings who are worth making
a fuss over.

<p>

Part of the reason why Mrs. Rudisill's tea party had such an effect
on me is that it caused me to ask:  Who will be the Betty Rudisill
in the lives of my future grandchildren when my kids send their
kids to come visit us?  And in what child's life will my wife
and I get to play the role of a Betty Rudisill?

<p>

I find myself not being able to answer those kinds of questions
as easily as I suspect my parent's generation answered them. 
And given the go-go pace of modern life, the growing transience
of our population, the weakening of community ties, and the waning
appreciation for those who quietly invest their lives in other
people, I suspect that many of my peers would struggle with these
questions as well.

<p>

In a recent article, author John Whitehead observed:

<p><blockquote>

<i>The entire concept of the neighborhood is lost to us, and our
children are growing up in a bland world.  Rarely can a child
see people working at their trades, for everyone is out of sight.
Children can no longer listen to community talk at the post office
or at the park bench and there are no abandoned houses, barns,
or attics that children can safely explore.  Forced by the many
dangers of an empty home and neighborhood to remain behind locked
doors, children wile away their hours after school by interacting
with their computers and video games.  Cyberspace has replaced
the neighborhoods familiar to their grandparents.</i>

</blockquote><p>

Now, again, don't misunderstand me.  I am not saying -- nor was
Uhlenberg saying -- that we should devote more attention to rebuilding
strong neighborhoods and communities than we do to rebuilding
strong families.  Quite the opposite.  But the health of the nuclear
family is significantly affected by the strength of the surrounding
community.  In fact, even if we were only concerned about families,
we would need to give attention to the strength and health of
the social networks in which families are enmeshed.

<p>

In this regard, I was struck several years ago by some surprising
differences in divorce rates by region.  Interestingly, divorce
rates tend to be significantly higher in the Sunbelt (and even
Bible Belt) regions of the country than in the Northeast or Midwest.
There are a number of reasons for this, but University of Texas
sociologist Norval Glenn has determined that the single greatest
predictor of divorce rates in a community is the degree to which
the people are rooted in a larger social network.  In areas of
the Midwest and the Northeast where you have more stable communities
-- where you often have strong ethnic communities -- divorce rates
tend to be lower because there is a surrounding web of individuals
who are working to try to help that couple succeed.  In more transient
areas of the country, particularly in areas where there is low
church participation, divorce rates tend to be higher because
many couples are existing very much as Uhlenberg described --
in isolation, lacking some type of supporting network to help
them and to challenge them and to hold them accountable.

<p>

I must say here that Dr. Uhlenberg not only can speak to this
question from his professional observations as a scholar.  But
he can also speak to this concern from his own personal experience.
I don't know about you, but my family has taken a great interest
in the new television show, <I>Second Noah,</I> that depicts the
life of a couple that is based here in Tampa.  The couple has
a rather unique story.  Over the course of time, they have adopted
eight or 10 different kids of varying races and backgrounds to
raise as their own.

<p>

In many ways, that television show closely resembles the life
of Peter Uhlenberg and his wife Pam.  Over the last two decades,
they have adopted a dozen or so children.  Some of these children
have physical handicaps; some come from mixed racial backgrounds;
some have learning disabilities; some have no special needs --
except the need for a devoted Mom and Dad. If you wish to pay
tribute to the kinds of sacrifices that Peter Uhlenberg and his
wife are making in their lives with those kids, they will be quick
to tell you that it would not be possible for them to be involved
in the work that they are doing in their home were it not for
the surrounding network of support that they get from the local
church congregation in which they play a part.  Indeed, there
are members of that congregation that have established big brother
or big sister relationships with different members of the Uhlenberg
family.  I'm sure that they are right-that if it were not for
that supportive network, the really heroic work that Peter Uhlenberg
and his wife are doing would  be very difficult, if not impossible.

<p>

The third lesson, then, that I think we can learn from Peter and
his wife (and his entire congregation, for that matter) is this
-- if we hope to turn things around in this country, if we hope
to see America become the shining city on a hill, it's going to
cost us something.  It's going to cost us personally. It's going
to require sacrificial love on our part, if I can use the &quot;L&quot;-word.
I'm not speaking of the hollow, feel-good love that was celebrated
by the '60s counterculture when Peter Uhlenberg was a student
at the University of California at Berkeley.  I'm speaking about
the gritty, unconditional, sacrificial love that he and his wife
have found and are now sharing with their kids.  That is a love
that is costly, to be sure, but it is a love that offers great
rewards.

<p>

I don't know about you, but I am very much looking forward to
the Olympics that will take place later this year.  I always set
aside time to view them because I'm interested in seeing who will
show themselves to be the fastest sprinter or the highest jumper
or the longest javelin thrower.  But the greatest honor that is
reserved at the Olympics goes not to one of these individuals
who has managed to develop a specialized skill to a greater extent
than anyone else.  The greatest honor goes to two athletes; one
in the men's division called a decathlete who participates in
10 different events, and the other to a female heptathlete who
participates in seven different athletic events.  Now these athletes
cannot outperform everyone on the planet in every single one of
these categories.  Instead, they are the athletes best able to
outperform others in a combination of them all.  They are, in
a sense, the best all-around or most well-rounded athletes.

<p>

We live in a day when 15 minutes or more of fame is quite often
available to anyone who can excel in a single area of life --
even if that success comes at the expense of meeting more important
responsibilities in other areas of life. In many ways, then,
the challenge for each of us personally is not just to seek to
make an important contribution in our work, or in our neighborhood,
or in our churches or synagogues, or in our homes.  It is instead
to seek to make an important contribution in all of these areas
simultaneously.  The challenge for us is to strive to be as well
rounded as the decathlete or the heptathlete, never allowing our
pursuit of excellence in one area to come at the expense of the
others.

<p>

Peter Uhlenberg, in my mind, is meeting that challenge.  He is
a whole man.  If the serious social problems Uhlenberg tracks
in his work are to be reversed, we will need to become more like
him -- people who not only wring our hands about various social
problems, but people who take personal action in our own homes
and neighborhoods to address these serious problems.

<p>

Thank you very much.

<p>
-- 4/20/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>William R. Mattox, Jr. is vice president for policy at the
Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and
educational organization.</i>

<p>

