<title>FAMILY TIME: WHAT PARENTS WANT</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>FAMILY TIME:<br>
WHAT PARENTS WANT</h2></center>

<hr size = 3 width = 50%>

<p>

<ul>

<li>A 1993 Families and Work Institute study found that 66 percent
of the 3,381 adults surveyed nationwide wanted more time with
their children.[1]

<p>

<li>Parents today spend only 17 hours per week with their children,
40 percent less than in 1965, according to a University of Maryland
study.[2]

<p>

<li>A recent <I>Newsweek</I> poll found that one half of all parents
feel that they don't spend enough time with their children.[3]

<p>

<li>Sixty-six percent of employed parents with children ages 18
and under indicated that they did not have enough time with their
children, and another 50 percent indicated that they did not have
enough time with their spouses.[4]

<p>

<li>Thirty-five percent of all workers with children would be
willing to change jobs in order to receive flexible scheduling
around their home concerns.[5]

<p>

<li>The 44 percent of parents who do not feel that they spend
enough time with their children cite work as the most frequent
culprit.[6]

<p>

<li>Half of America's moms have said no to job advancement compared
with only 29 percent of dads. This trend is more prevalent in
younger mothers, where 62 percent have turned down promotions
in favor of spending more time with their children. However, two
out of three dads say they have not turned down a job promotion
in favor of spending more time with their kids.[7]

<p>

<li>Half of all fathers feel that they do not spend enough time
with their children.[8]

<p>

<li>A 1995 Gallup poll found that nearly half of all parents feel
that they spend too little time with their children. Fewer than
one-third of these respondents ate dinner together on a regular
basis.[9]

<p>

<li>The overwhelming choice for weekend family activities seems
to be spending time with children. Parents' top four choices for
weekend activities were &quot;talking with children,&quot; taking 
&quot;care of children,&quot; going on &quot;trips with children,&quot; 
and playing &quot;games with children.&quot; Unfortunately, by 1986 
parents actually had 10 fewer hours per week to spend with their 
children then they did in 1960.[10]

</ul><p>

-- 1/22/96

<p><hr><p>

<h3><center>ENDNOTES</center></h3>

<ol><font size=-1>

<p>

