<html>

<title>FAMILY TIME: WHAT AMERICANS WANT</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>FAMILY TIME:<br>
WHAT AMERICANS WANT</h2></center>

<hr size = 3 width = 50%>

<p>

<ul>

<li>A 1993 study conducted by the Families and Work Institute
found that 66 percent of the 3,381 adults surveyed nationwide
wanted more time with their children.[1]

<p>

<li>&quot;The Changing Workforce,&quot; a national study conducted
by the Families and Work Institute, found that 66 percent of employed
parents with children ages 18 and under indicated that they did
not have enough time with their children, and another 50 percent
indicated that they did not have enough time with their spouses.[2]

<p>

<li>A 1991 Gallup poll found that when asked what was most important
to them, Americans ranked family life and betterment of society
above &quot;having a nice home, car, and other belongings.&quot;[3]

<p>

<li>On average, parents today spend only 17 hours per week with
their children, according to a University of Maryland study.[4] This
is roughly 40 percent less than in 1965.

<p>

<li>A recent <I>Newsweek</I> poll found that one half of all parents
feel that they don't spend enough time with their children.[5]

<p>

<li>Sixty percent of all employees consider their jobs effect
on their personal or family life to be a &quot;very important&quot;
factor in their decision to take the job. This is not surprising,
as 42 percent of all U.S. workers have children under 18 years
of age living at home. Furthermore, 32 percent of all U.S. workers
have children under 13 years of age at home, and in 66 percent
of these families both parents work (18 percent for kids under
6 years of age).[6]

<p>

<li>According to a survey commissioned by the Massachusetts Mutual
Life Insurance Company, half of all fathers feel that they do
not spend enough time with their children.[7]

<p>

<li>Forty-four percent of women would prefer more family time
over higher pay in their jobs, while 48 percent of men would prefer
more time than money.[8]

<p>

<li>Most workers (57 percent) would trade early retirement in
favor of family time, according to a survey commissioned by the
Family Research Council. Roughly a third (36 percent) said they
prefer to work longer hours now and retire sooner.[9]

<p>

<li>The overwhelming choice for weekend family activities seems
to be spending time with children. Parents top four choices for
weekend activities were &quot;talking with children,&quot; taking
&quot;care of children,&quot; going on &quot;trips with children,&quot;
and playing &quot;games with children.&quot; Unfortunately, by
1986 parents actually had 10 fewer hours per week to spend with
their children than they did in 1960.[10]

<p>

<li>A 1995 Wharton School study found that people who placed high
importance on finding the right spouse and creating a good family
life actually ended up earning more money than those who were
willing to sacrifice home life for their careers. Peter Capelli,
a management professor at the Wharton School, explains that building
a good family life is particularly important early in careers
as &quot;that's where the serious mistakes get made. People who
didn't take time for their families spend a lot of time putting
Band-Aids on family problems&quot; later on, which hurts work
performance and commitment.[11]

<p>

<li>Seventy-eight percent of Americans feel that a father should
choose to spend more time with his children if given the choice
between that and earning more money for his family, and 75 percent
felt that a mother should choose to spend more time with her children
if given the same choice.[12]

</ul><p>

-- 1/24/96

<p><hr><p>

<h3><center>ENDNOTES</center></h3>

<ol><font size=-1>

<p>

<li>Sauerwein, Kristina.  &quot;'90's Family; The Friend Trend.&quot;
<I>Los Angeles Times</I> 31 August 1994; home ed., part E3, column
2.

