<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Washington Report:  June 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"></td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>June 1996</h3><p>
<img src="red-line.gif">
</center><p>
WASHINGTON REPORT<p>
<a href="#black">Republicans and the "Black Vote"</a><br>
<a href="#florida">The Re-Structuring of Florida's Congressional Districts</a><br>
<a href="#franks">Gary Franks and Partisan Politics</a><br>
<a href="#sex">Defense of Marriage Act</a><br>
<ul>
<p>

<li><a name="black"></a>Rep. J.C. Watts, one of two black Republican House members and a co-chairman of Senator Bob Dole's Republican presidential campaign, has accused the party of not trying harder to win over black voters.<p>
The freshman congressman, a former all-American college football star at the University of Oklahoma, said Apr. 23 that the party would never become the majority party unless it developed a strategy to get more black and minority voters.<P>
Blacks have overwhelmingly been supporting Democrats in modern elections.<P>
"I do believe to this day, that the Republican Party will never become the majority party until we regain our legacy as a party for minority Americans," Watts said.<P>
Watts, a congressman from Oklahoma, told the conservative Heritage Foundation in a speech and question and answer period, that the party is not doing enough on an "outreach" program to get minority voters.<P>
"There has to be a long-term, orchestrated, organized effort to say where do we want to be two years from now, where do we want to be four years ago, five years ago, ten years ago," he said.<P>
He said "we must have an organized outreach strategy by the RNC (Republican National Committee), and even the think tanks," he said.<P>
Watts said the party often presents "white papers" and other ideas on attracting minorities. "But we put forth no organized effort on outreach, none."<P>
Watts, who has one of the most conservative voting records in Congress, said the Republican Party reaches out to small business people even though some differ with the party.<P>
"Should we not do the same with the black community?" he said.<P>
He suggested a Republican outreach program should stress that Republican policies in Congress such as welfare reform and a balanced budget would help black Americans.<P>
The party should act now to get more blacks into the party, he said.  He estimated that only eight to 12 percent of blacks voted Republican in 1992 and said the goal should be improved to 15 to 18 percent this year, 19 to 25 percent in the year 2000 and 30 percent in eight years.<P>
There was no immediate response from a Republican Party spokesman to the speech from Watts, one of about one dozen co-chairmen of the Dole campaign.<P>

<li><a name="florida"></a>A federal court threw out Florida's 23 congressional boundaries Apr. 17, ruling that an Orlando-area district was illegally drawn to elect a black lawmaker.  The decision shook the state's political landscape and could threaten the only three black members of Congress elected from Florida this century.  <P>
"It took us 127 years for Florida to elect an African-American member of Congress, so this is just the beginning, not the end," said Rep. Corrine Brown (D).  In nullifying Brown's horseshoe-shaped, 14-county congressional district, the judges discarded Florida's entire congressional map.  <P>
In the majority decision, U.S. District Judges Maurice Paul and Roger Vinson concluded the 3rd congressional district cannot survive the present constitutional equal protection challenge.  But they cautioned, "This decision should not be interpreted as  turning back the clock' on the gains made by African-American voters."  The panel's only black judge, Joseph Hatchett, was the lone dissenter. <P>
The ruling ordered the Florida Legislature to draw new congressional districts by May 22, or the federal panel will create a new map for the 1996 elections.  Particularly difficult will be redrawing the 3rd congressional district, which touches six others.  The Central Florida Republicans who will will inherit part of Brown's district are Reps. Fowler (4th District), Stearns (6th District), Mica (7th District) and McCollum (8th District).  Brown will serve the remainder of her term, but will have to run in a new congressional district in November.  <P>
The ruling could force legislators to address the racial balance in at least two other districts.  The other congressional districts are currently represented by Alcee Hastings (D-23) and Carrie Meek (D-17). <P>

<li><a name="franks"></a>In a new book about his life and experiences on Capitol Hill, Rep. Gary Franks of Connecticut, who in 1990 became the first black Republican elected to the House in 58 years, writes, "For too long, the African-American community has been focused on how  we have been done wrong."<P>
But current and former Congressional Black Caucus members are furious at Franks' focus in his book on how he has "been done wrong" by black House Democrats allegedly angry with his conservative views, the Hartford Courant reported April 28.  "I was absolutely shocked and dismayed when I read the mischaracterizations," former Con-gressional Black Caucus Chairman Kweisi Mfume, D-Md., now the NAACP president, told the Courant after reading excerpts of the book.<P>
Rep. Earl Hilliard (D-Ala.) called Franks a "liar," and current CBC Chairman Donald Payne (D-N.J.) said, "I never saw any organized conspiracy against him."<P>
Throughout his book, Searching for the Promised Land: An African-American's Optimistic Odyssey, which is scheduled for publication in June, Franks offers a litany of slights by black House Democrats, even saying he was "shunned" and "blacklisted."<P>
Rep. Corrine Brown (D-Fla.) frequently moved away from him at CBC lunches, Franks contended, while Rep. Ronald Dellums (D-Calif.) once shouted insults in his face while they were on the House floor.  And on a bus ride to the Capitol from the White House, where the caucus had just met with President Clinton, Franks told how alone he felt.  "I truly felt like the invisible man of the old Jim Crow South," Franks wrote.  "I sat amidst a bus full of people who literally wished I would just disappear."<P>
Franks wrote that he positioned himself in the middle of the bus and "sure enough, when everybody had settled down, there was a cordon of empty seats around me."  Franks thought to himself, "How many black people had sat like this, shunned by their own people?"<P>
Mfume and Payne remembered no such shunning.  "I remember Gary getting on the bus and engaging in a give-and-take with other members, joking with them," Mfume told the Courant.  "It's hard to imagine he sat alone; we had 40 members and the bus was not that big."<P>
Franks also charged Mfume and other caucus members attempted to silence him during the meeting with Clinton.<P>
When he arrived to the House in 1991, Franks was an important ambassador from the CBC to then-President Bush, he wrote.  But CBC members' moods changed after the 1992 election, when more blacks were elected, and at the same time, the shape of some majority-black districts came under legal fire.<P>
Franks later testified in favor of challenges to the majority-black districts that were drawn to help elect several members of the CBC.  When he arrived to testify, Franks said Brown "turned and stared coldly into my eyes."<P>
Encounters with CBC members are a small part of Franks' book, which chronicles the 43-year-old's life.<P>
Franks has received a $100,000 advance, and under House rules can keep any royalties from the book's sale.  But he said he intends to give a portion of any royalties to nonprofit groups in Meriden and Waterbury, Conn.<P>
The Courant reported that many mentioned in the book disputed the accuracy of Franks' recollections. Franks, meanwhile, said he did not want to discuss his book at this time.  "He was never treated the way he said," said Rep. John Conyers (D-Mich.), the senior CBC member.  Payne added, "Gary thinks people pay more attention to him than they really did."<P>
But Brown, whom Franks had accused of shunning him at the luncheons, said Franks was not too far off.  "I didn't want to sit by him," she said.  "I like to sit by people of kindred spirits."<P>

<li><a name="sex"></a>A bill backed by three Republican lawmakers would keep same-sex marriage from becoming legal whatever the outcome of a controversial gay-rights case in Hawaii.<P>
A draft of the bill being circulated among members of Congress would outlaw any future gay marriages by defining marriage as a "legal union between one man and one women" in federal law.<P>
The bill, titled the "Defense of Marriage Act," sponsored by Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) also would give states the authority to reject the legality of same-sex marriages performed in any other state.  Rep. Steven Largent (R-Okla.) and Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.) are listed as co-sponsors of the bill.<P>
"Is America willing to require businesses to have family benefits for homosexual couples," said Largent in a May 8 statement, "to have children taught in school that homosexual relationships are the moral equivalent of traditional marriage, and to endorse the adoption of children by homosexual couples?  Is America willing to go down that road?"<P>
The Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the Anaheim, Calif.-based Traditional Values Coalition, said he helped draft the bill in response to a court case that could make Hawaii the first state to recognize gay marriages.<P>
"This is the beginning of a cultural meltdown if you have homosexual marriage sanctioned by the court," Sheldon said May 7.  "When the federal government says homosexuality is valid enough for marriage, then you are sending a message to the children, you're sending a message to the culture and you are about ready to move yourself into a serious cultural meltdown."<P>
Gary Bauer, President of the Family Research Council, agreed.  The Defense of Marriage Act "is one of the most crucial pieces of legislation to be considered in this or any year.  This is a cultural watershed," said Gary Bauer.  "Will America move to protect marriage--the foundation of civilization--or will America become the first nation to destroy marriage?  At stake is nothing less than the future of the nation and the well being of our children."<P>
The Hawaii Supreme Court ruled in May 1993 that the denial of marriage licenses to three same-sex couples was discriminatory under the state's Equal Rights Amendment.  Limiting the right of marriage to heterosexuals can be justified only if the state can prove a "compelling government interest," the Hawaii court said.<P>
The state Supreme Court remanded the case to a lower court for a trial at which the state will try to show a compelling interest.<P>
This legally and politically explosive question has touched off legislative efforts in more than half the states to counter any Hawaiian sanction of same-sex marriages.<P>
Thirty-three state legislatures have taken up bills prohibiting same-sex marriage, and eight states have passed those measures into law.<P>
The bills have been defeated, withdrawn or killed in 17 states, and measures are still pending in eight more.<P>
"The heart of family life is marriage," Bauer said.  "It brings the two sexes together in a unique legal, social, economic and spiritual union--no other relationship provides society with the benefits that marriage does.  As we have drifted from the defense of marriage, we have experienced severe social and economic problems, and now, marriage is under attack as never before.  If the one-man, one-woman definition of marriage is broken, there is no logical stopping point for continuing the assault on marriage.  No civilization has ever introduced a counterfeit definition of marriage, and those who have allowed the family to be weakened have not survived.<P>



</ul>
<p><p>
<center>[ <a href="/nmp/">Headway Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ] </center></BODY>
</HTML>
