<DOCOLDNO>IA031-000660-B003-330</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.conservative.org:80/nmp/wr-5-96.html 204.71.237.88 19970209101936 text/html 12592
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 10:20:22 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 16-May-96 20:54:15 GMT
Content-length: 12406
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  May 1996</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>May 1996</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>
WASHINGTON REPORT<P>

<A HREF="#colin">The Return of Colin Powell?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#tenn">An Open Seat in Tennessee</A><BR>
<A HREF="#SJC">Pronouncement on Voting Rights from the SJC</A><BR>
<A HREF="#church">Flames of Hatred</A><BR>
<A HREF="#perot">Perot's Drifting Support</A><BR>
<A HREF="#cc">Christian Coalition Embraces Urban Outreach</A><BR>


<ul>
<P>
<LI><A NAME="colin"></A>During the past month, family members of Colin 
Powell, who is often touted as a potential running mate 
for the presumptive GOP nominee, Senator Robert Dole, 
have been vocal about their feelings concerning the 
retired general being on the Republican ticket.<P>
Alma Powell says she was frightened by the attention 
generated when her husband was considering a run for the 
presidency--including hate mail and strangers ringing 
the doorbell.<P>
"A black man running for president is going to be in 
a dangerous position," she told Ladies Home Journal in 
its May issue.  "I did not want him to run," she said.  
"I told him that from the very beginning."
"I dont want to describe the hate mail weve 
gotten," Mrs. Powell added.<P>
"You think everybody loves Colin Powell.  Everybody 
doesnt like Colin Powell.  One day I got two letters--
one telling me what a wonderful man I was married to and 
how much the country needed him; the other said Colin 
Powell is a scum bag and proceeded to list all his 
evils."<P>
She added: "Im a very private person and it was all 
a little scary.  Strangers would ring the doorbell and 
ask for Colin."<P>
One man who showed up "said he had driven all the way 
from Florida to beg him to run for president," Mrs. 
Powell recalled.  When asked how he knew their address, 
"the man said hes read that we lived in McLean, Va., so 
he had just poked around the neighborhood, asking 
questions.  That makes you very vulnerable."
She said her husband could accomplish more as a 
private person than as a government official.<P>
A few weeks earlier, Michael Powell, Colins son 
said: "If he didnt want the top job, why should anyone 
think he would want the second job when, in my opinion, 
he could have had it all.  Why would he want to play 
second fiddle?. . .He firmly believes he does not want 
to do this now."<P>
For his part, the retired general has said repeatedly 
that he is not interested in the number two slot.
But some old political hands have said that "if Dole 
presses, Powell could resist only so long."  But Mickey 
Edwards, an Oklahoma Republican and former member of 
Congress, said:  "The point will come when he cant say 
no because he is a man who responds to duty."  But 
sources close to the family said that there was still no 
compelling reason for Powell to run for vice president.<P>
One family friend reportedly said:  "I dont think 
its sufficient to say for Republicans to fail to regain 
the White House [it] is a national disaster. . . Whats 
in it for him?  He doesnt need money; he doesnt need 
any of them.  They have nothing to give him, nothing to 
offer him.  Any decision he makes is based on pure 
conviction."<P><A NAME="tenn"></A>
<LI>Saying he wants "to go out on top," Democratic 
Congressman Harold Ford announced Apr. 11 he would not 
seek re-election to a 12th term.
The Tennessee Democrat joins 27 other House Democrats 
and 17 Re-publicans who have decided to retire from the 
House while a record 13 senators, including five 
Republicans and eight Democrats, are making an exodus 
from the Senate.  <P>
Fords departure creates an open seat and clears the 
way for his Republican challenger, Rod DeBerry, to pick 
up where he left off in the 1994 election.  DeBerry 
received 42 percent against Ford in 1994 and is running 
for the seat again this year.  Tennessees 9th 
Congressional District includes most of Memphis and a 
small part of suburban Shelby County.<P>
"I want to go out on top.  I think the public opinion 
polls show Im stronger than ever in my career," said 
Ford when he announced his retirement.<P>
But Ford, 50, said that after 22 years in Washington, 
it was time for a new face to represent Tennessees 
ninth district and that it was time for him to return to 
Memphis and be a part of that city.<P>
Ford has rarely faced a serious challenge for re-
election.  He was indicted on federal bank fraud charges 
in 1987 and was re-elected three times before he was 
acquitted at trial in 1993.<P>
The Democratic congressmans attempt to pick his 
successor--his 26-year-old son, Harold Jr.--has placed 
him at odds with Mayor W. W. Herenton, who says the 
younger Ford lacks the experience to represent Memphis 
in Congress.  Ford Jr. is about to graduate from the 
University of Michigan law school.<P>
Herenton has accused Ford of using "his political 
clout to exploit the economically downtrodden and divide 
the city for his political gain."  The Memphis mayor is 
organizing a committee to find an alternative candidate 
for the Democratic primary in August.<P>
While nepotism is practiced regularly in politics, it 
has had limited success in Congress as far as electing a 
retiring Congressmembers spouse or children.  Most 
recently, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has never held 
elected office, helped his son, Jesse Jackson, Jr., get 
elected to Congress from Illinois.  But Rep. Walter 
Tucker III (D-Calif.), who resigned in December rather 
than face expulsion after his conviction on extortion 
and tax evasion charges, failed in getting his wife 
elected to his seat, even after he endorsed her as his 
successor.<P>
<A NAME="SJC"></A>
<LI>The Supreme Court handed the Republican Party of 
Virginia defeat March 27, ruling that it must get 
clearance under the Voting Rights Act to charge a fee to 
delegates who want to attend a nominating convention. 
The 5-4 decision also allowed three former University of 
Virginia law students to file suit in federal court on 
the grounds that the $45 fee charged for the 1994 
convention which nominated Oliver North amounted to a 
poll tax.  <P>
Two of the students who challenged the fee refused to 
pay and did not attend the convention; one was given 
money by the North campaign and did attend.  E. Duncan 
Getchell, Jr., an attorney for the Virginia GOP, said he 
hopes that as the law continues to develop in this area 
that the views of the dissenters will prevail. <P>
The high court overturned an earlier decision made in 
federal court, which held that the federal clearance 
only applied to primaries, not nominating conventions; 
the court found the convention to be tantamount to a 
primary.  Justice John Paul Stevens, joined by Ruth 
Bader Ginsburg, wrote one majority opinion, while 
Justices Stephen Breyer, Sandra Day OConnor and David 
Souter joined in separate opinions to complete the 
majority.  Dissenting were Chief Justice William 
Rehnquist and Justices Anthony Kennedy, Antonin Scalia 
and Clarence Thomas. <P>
Thomas and Scalia accused the majority of trampling 
political parties freedom of association.  But the 
practical impact of the decision may be limited because 
only Virginia and Alabama, among states subject to pre-
clearance, authorize party conventions for choosing 
nominees. <P>
This year the Virginia GOP is scheduled to have a 
primary.  The choice of whether to hold a primary or 
convention is given to the incumbent in Virginia, and 
Sen. John Warner (R) chose a primary, a choice widely 
regarded as one that enhances his chances of getting the 
nomination against the opposition of more conservative 
party leaders.<P>
<A NAME="church"></A>
<LI>As a result of the efforts of Edmund Peterson, 
chairman of Project 21, a Washington, D.C.-based public 
policy group promoting conservative black leadership, 
several Republican members of Congress have signed and 
forwarded a letter to U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno 
urging her to investigate the bombings of black churches 
in the South which have occurred over the past few 
years.<P>
"We are gravely concerned over news reports of a wave 
of church burnings in several southern states," began 
the letter, which was dated Mar. 1.  "Eleven churches 
have been vic-timized by arson since last December 22, 
and a total of nineteen churches have been burned since 
the beginning of 1995."<P>
"We urge you to mobilize the resources of the Justice 
Department, to the extent possible under the law, to 
help state and local law enforcement agencies apprehend 
and convict the perpetrators of these acts," the letter 
continued.<P>
The letter was signed by several GOP Congressmen from 
Southern states, including Reps. Sue Myrick of North 
Carolina, Curt Weldon of Florida, Lindsey Graham of 
South Carolina and Charlie Norwood of Georgia.  Others 
signing the letter included Reps. J.C. Watts and Steve 
Largent of Oklahoma, Helen Chenoweth of Idaho and James 
Talent of Missouri.<P>
Peterson, who has been pleased with the response of 
the legislators to his request thus far, said action by 
Congress is imperative.  "We must not forget that 
churches are more than buildings; when churches burn, a 
piece of our freedom is also extinguished in flames of 
hatred."<P>
<A NAME="perot"></A>
<LI> The most recent USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll showed 
Ross Perots current support is younger, poorer and less 
educated than they were in 1992--and that could be bad 
news.  The poll shows he is losing support among those 
most likely to vote: older, wealthier and more-educated. 
Perots support is down to 16 percent from the 19 
percent he received in 1992, but is growing among women 
and minorities, which his supporters argue indicates 
Perots message is resonating among a broader spectrum 
of the electorate.  Perots recent speeches on college 
campuses in Texas and Florida are part of an effort to 
attract younger voters who seem to be gravitating more 
towards Perot than they did in 1992. <P>
Reform Party Director Russ Verney called college 
campuses "fertile territory," because they are populated 
by first-time voters with no party allegiance.  Young 
voters also tend to be most frustrated with Congress 
failure to pass a balanced budget amendment, reform 
Medicare and Medicaid and approve term limits.  Young 
voters are also concerned about corporate downsizing and 
international trade deals they fear have shifted jobs 
abroad.<P>
Democrat pollster Peter Hart said:  "All I would 
simply tell you is it is a very different electorate 
that is going to be with Ross Perot in 1996 than was 
there in 1992 and a lot of these new voters would be in 
Bill Clintons column if Ross Perot were not on the 
ballot."  <P><A NAME="cc"></A>
<LI>Nationally syndicated radio talk show host and 
outspoken urban activist Rev. Earl Jackson has been 
named National Liaison of Christian Coalitions Urban 
Development Program.  Jackson will play a lead role in 
explaining the mission of the pro-life, pro-family group 
to minority voters and will work to expand the 
distribution of the Christian Coalitions non-partisan 
voter education material in African-American churches 
across the country.<P>
"We have been working for years to carry our message 
into minority churches," said Ralph Reed, Executive 
Director of the Christian Coalition.  "With Rev. Earl 
Jackson on the team, our urban development program will 
reach even greater numbers."<P>
Jackson, a Baptist minister, Harvard Law School 
graduate and host of the nationally syndicated radio 
talk show, "Earl Jackson Across America," started work 
with the Christian Coalitions Urban Development Project 
at the end of March.<P>
Presently, there are 250,000 churches distributing 
Christian Coalitions non-partisan voter education 
literature.  Approximately 10 percent of those churches 
are minority houses of worship.<P>



</ul>
<P><P>
