<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  March 1996</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>March 1996</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>

<a name="table"><b>Table of Contents</b></a>
<p>


WASHINGTON REPORT

<ul><li>Black conservative groups said January 15 they are working closely with Congress to develop legislation that brings back traditional family values and improves the government's approach to 
helping the poor.<p>
&quot;The year 1996 has the potential to go down in history as the year of real change in government policy,&quot; said Star Parker, president of the Coalition on Urban Affairs, at a press conference in downtown Los Angeles.<p>
In response to a Black Contract with America sent to Congress by black conservatives in early 1995, House Speaker Newt Gingrich appointed a Minority Issues Task Force to organize hearings and policy development on minority issues.<p>
The task force developed the Project for American Renewal, which outlines several family and community empowerment bills scheduled for congressional votes by mid-spring.<p>
One example is the Family Reconciliation Act, which requires counseling and a waiting period for divorces involving children under 12 years old, and eliminates public funding for divorce except in cases of abuse.  The government-funded Legal Services Corp. provides help to the poor for divorces.<p>
Jesse Peterson, founder of the Brotherhood Organization of a New Destiny, said the black community needs to focus on the family and teach children to work and be self-reliant, not depend on government programs like welfare.<p>
&quot;People who are on welfare should be required to work--we need to move away from having government do everything, since it rarely does anything well,&quot; Peterson said.<p>
Peterson said conservatives in Congress realize the current system is &quot;a miserable failure&quot; and are suggesting a more grassroots effort to help single parents through their family, church and community.<p>
Another bill would allow low-income families to receive vouchers that enables them to send their child to the public or private school of their choice, instead of forcing them to attend academically poor inner-city schools.<p>
&quot;Granting parents the ability to choose the best school for their children is the best measure we can take to improve the quality of education in the public schools,&quot; said Americans for Family Values founder Ezola Foster.<p>
&quot;It is the first and most important step to take,&quot; said Foster, who is also a Los Angeles public school teacher.  &quot;Not surprisingly, it is not the liberals but conservatives in Congress who are proposing we take this step.&quot;<p>
Edmund Peterson (not related to Jesse Peterson), chairman of the black leadership group Project 21, said he and the other black conservative leaders chose Martin Luther King, Jr.'s birthday to discuss their political agenda to encourage people to reflect on issues of family 
values.<p>

<li>The Justice Department said Feb. 7 that it is investigating whether fires set to black churches in Alabama, Tennessee and unspecified other states were racially motivated.  &quot;We take these matters very seriously,&quot; says the department's Myron Marlin.<p>
Arsonists have damaged at least 17 churches in Alabama, Louisiana, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas since January 1995.<p>
Pro football star Reggie White is an associate pastor of Inner City Baptist Church in east Knoxville, Tenn., which was destroyed Jan. 8.  Arsonists left racist messages at the scene.  The 124-year-old Salem Baptist Church near Fruitland, Tenn., had been set ablaze a week earlier.<p>
Edmund Peterson, chairman of Project 21, a Washington, D.C.-based public policy group  promoting con-servative black leadership, addressed a letter to Republican members of Congress asking them to speak out as public servants against &quot;this threat to the religious rights of millions of Americans.&quot;<p>
 	&quot;In the past, the press has portrayed Republicans as uncaring of minorities and their concerns,&quot; the letter continued.  &quot;This is an opportunity for Republicans to prove them wrong once again.&quot;<p>

 <li>	As Washington policymakers struggle to find solutions to America's major social problems, they should consider the enormous contribution religion can make toward solving them, according to a Heritage Foundation analyst.<p>
In a paper released January 25, Patrick Fagan, an expert in family and social issues at Heritage, says nearly every major study on the impact of religion demonstrates its positive impact on a host of social problems.  Religion, the majority of studies onclude, &quot;is the resource 
that most powerfully addresses the major social problems confronting the nation,&quot; according to Fagan, the William H.G. FitzGerald fellow.<p>
Fagan presents a summary of the social science literature, which reveals that religious practice strengthens the family and brings satisfaction to marriage; helps poor people move out of poverty; aids substantially in the formation of personal moral judgement; and inoculates individuals against such social problems such as suicide, drug abuse, out-of-wedlock births, 
crime and divorce.<p>
&quot;Renowned historians and philosophers have always known that the character of a social order is, in larger part, determined by its religious roots.  Social science cannot prove that religion, or religion in any varying expressions, is true. But the professional literature of the modern social sciences has shown religious practice to have positive social consequences,&quot; Fagan says.<p>
Another important study of strong families, conducted in the 1970s and 1980s by a pair of University of Nebraska professors, found that &quot;84 percent of these families identified religion as an important contributor to the strength of their families.&quot;  The same study also indicated that 
&quot;parents who attended church frequently cited the significance of religion in rearing their children and in providing moral guidance.&quot;<p>
Ongoing studies by Arizona State University West demonstrate that religious belief and practice encourage optimism among socially at-risk children.  Among the findings: Students who attend church weekly or more frequently are more optimistic about their futures; have better relationships with their parents; are more likely to dismiss racism as an obstacle to reaching their goals; and are more likely to see themselves in control of their own futures, not as victims of oppression.<p>
Armed with such evidence about the positive benefits of religious practice, Fagan says it is time for policymakers to stop ignoring the role religion plays in the welfare of the nation.  &quot;Given the growing crisis in out-of-wedlock births and their resultant effects, such as huge social 
and economic costs, this research should be of major interest to policymakers,&quot; he says.<p>

<li> The House voted Jan. 31 on a bill that would create a $5 million private school choice program in Washington, D.C.<p>
Low-income students would be eligible for private school scholarships of up to $3,000 a year for tuition and $1,500 for after-school activities "to enhance their achievement," according to a summary of the deal finalized by House and Senate negotiators.<p>
One key change from the House bill would give Washington's city council veto power over the parameters for allocating scholarships, the summary said.<p>
Students whose family income is below the poverty level would qualify for $3,000 scholarships, and students whose family income is 85 percent above the poverty level could get up to $1,500 for tuition.<p>
&quot;It will give these kids and their parents a choice that they've never had. This will also, in my opinion, be the catalyst to transform the district's public schools into better educational institutions,&quot; said Rep. James Walsh (R-N.Y.) chairman of the Appropriations Subcommittee on 
the District.<p>
But Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, ranking Democrat on the Appropriations Committee, said he was concerned the bill would set a national precedent.  &quot;As soon as this bill is passed, you are then going to see organizations with an ideological agenda who will begin to pressure each and every school district in the country to follow the same model.&quot;<p>
The 2,000 vouchers are a small element of a 14-point reform package that is designed to arrest the appalling deterioration of the District's public schools.  Despite annual expenditures of $9,549 a year on each student, more than 50 percent of the district's high school seniors are 
functionally illiterate when they graduate.  Several local officials, including three city council members and the superintendent of schools, support the vouchers as a last-ditch effort to save some students.  Other reforms in the bill include the creation of 10 independent charter schools 
and a public boarding school, along with a requirement that students not be promoted to the next grade if they aren't prepared.<p>
But the voucher provision has attracted the ire of the National Education Association, which views the concept of parental choice with disdain.  Its favorite Senate Republican, Jim Jeffords of Vermont, grimly refused up until recently to let the entire D.C. appropriations bill out 
of a committee unless vouchers were stripped out and put to a separate vote.  But Senator Jeffords didn't count on the determination of D.C. parents and choice supporters.<p>
The D.C.-based Center for New Black Leadership noted that Senator Jeffords supported an existing voucher program in Vermont at the same time he was blocking similar opportunities for District children.<p>  
Two black parents, Karen Walker and Zaneta Simms, traveled to Vermont to accuse the Senator of &quot;standing in the schoolhouse door and telling black children they can't get in.&quot;  A group called the Coalition to Educate America flooded Vermont airwaves with radio ads featuring a plea from the two D.C. parents.<p>
Senator Jeffords called the ads &quot;garbage&quot; and said they had no effect on him.  But shortly after they began hitting the airwaves he accepted a compromise that gives the D.C. city council veto power over whether any money can be used for vouchers.  An attempt to strip vouchers 
from the bill failed in the House on a vote of 232 to 180.<p>
The Senate will vote on this measure on or around Feb. 27.  &quot;Now it is up to Senate Majority Leader Robert Dole to ensure there are enough votes for the bill,&quot; says Kevin Teasley of the Coalition to Educate America.</ul><p>

<P><P>
<center>[ <a href="/nmp/">Headway Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ] </center></BODY>

