<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  February 1996</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>February 1996</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>

<a name="table"><b>Table of Contents</b></a>
<p>

<P><ul>
<li>Democrats could pick up at least
two U.S. House seats in Georgia under a new electoral map that
increases the number of black voters in several congressional
districts now held by Republicans, party officials said Dec. 15.
<P>
But before they can erase a current
8-to-3 Republican majority in Georgia's congressional delegation,
Democratic leaders will have to overcome two obstacles, including
a potential backlash among black voters.
<P>
In addition, the American Civil
Liberties Union and the Justice Department are expected to appeal
the court-mandated district lines to the U.S. Supreme Court on
the grounds that the plan flies in the face of the 1965 Voting
Rights Act.
<P>
Black politicians, irate over
the loss of two black-majority districts, are threatening to revolt
against white Democratic leaders who they say are trying to negate
minority participation in the political process.
<P>
&quot;Overall, we now have excellent
opportunities to win several new seats,&quot; said Bill Florence,
communications director for the Georgia Democratic Party.
<P>
&quot;As much as I'd like to see
the delegation reversed to 8-3 for the Democrats, I really think
it's going to wind up 6-5. Who will have the majority, I don't
know. But it should break out to be pretty much even,&quot; he
said.
<P>
In the first judicial interpretation
of a new Supreme Court standard on redistricting, a federal court
in Augusta, Georgia, Dec. 13 broke up a concentration of black
voters that put two black members of Congress in office, Cynthia
McKinney in the 11th district and Sanford Bishop in the 2nd.
<P>
The ruling by a three-member judicial
panel pitted two Democrat-appointed judges who signed the plan
against a dissenting Republican. According to the panel's map,
districts represented by Republicans Jack Kingston, John Linder
and Charlie Norwood would have substantial black populations,
opening the door to potential Democratic gains.
<P>
&quot;That would be a kind of
classic white Democratic district of the 1970s and 1980s,&quot;
said Earl Black, a political science professor at Rice University.
<P>
Democrats also believe Bishop
can win reelection in his newly constituted district. The addition
of Macon, Ga., a Democratic stronghold, to the state's 8th district
could tip the balance in their favor there.
<P>
But Republicans and black politicians
say the strategy could backfire if black voters, who make up about
a third of the state's electorate, refuse to vote. The emergence
of black pri-mary candidates also could aid Republicans by leading
to racially polarized campaigns in the general election.
<P>
Linder, who expects to be reelected
in a new Republican 11th district, believes disenchantment among
blacks will be strong enough for his party to pick up new support
from the black community.
<P>
&quot;The blacks, seeing what
the Democrats are doing to them by taking away their seats, are
going to start looking around, I'm convinced,&quot; the Republican
congressman said. &quot;We're going to go aggressively into the
black churches in just the same way black candidates have done
for years.&quot;
<P>
State Representative Tyrone Brooks,
who heads the Georgia Association of Black Elected Officials,
said: &quot;The Democratic leaders and those two Democrat-appointed
judges think: 'Well, we'll realign these districts and these black
folks--they're ignorant--they're just going to go out and vote
for the Democrat on the ballot.' That is simply not going to happen.&quot;
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of Georgia
voters will appeal the court-mandated elimination of the two black-majority
voting districts.
<P>
But state officials appeared unlikely
to join the fight. A spokesman for Gov. Zell Miller said the governor
did not favor an appeal, saying the case already has cost Georgia
$1 million in legal fees.
<P>
There was no immediate word from
the lieutenant governor and speaker of the state House, both parties
to the case.
<P>
Laughlin McDonald, regional director
of the American Civil Liberties Union, said he will ask the same
judicial panel to stay the ruling on behalf of district voters,
black and white. But he expects to have to appeal the judge's
decision to the U.S. Supreme Court.
<P>
&quot;The plan offends basic fairness
and justice,&quot; said McDonald. &quot;We cannot predict the
future, of course, but we think we've got very strong arguments
to present to the Supreme Court.&quot;
<P>
McDonald called the panel's decision
&quot;retrogressive&quot; under the 1965 Voting Rights Act because
it leaves blacks worse off. He said the panel exceeded its judicial
power by drawing up a new electoral map rather than modifying
the former version.<BR>

<P>
<li>
The success of the Million Man March has inspired organizers to
plan an international Million Family March, the Rev. Benjamin
Chavis said.
<P>
&quot;The Million Man March brought
out a spirit of unity in the black community that was unequaled,&quot;
Chavis, former director of the NAACP, said in December after giving
a sermon at First Iconium Baptist Church in Atlanta. &quot;It
was natural that we try to build on that success.&quot;
<P>
The event, planned for Oct. 16,
1996, will include simultaneous, satellite-linked gatherings of
black families around the world. 
<P>
Chavis has said previously that
the anniversary of October's Million Man March on Washington will
be observed internationally.
<P>
Chavis, who helped organize this
year's march with Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan, said
the Nation of Islam will also be involved in next year's project.
<BR>

<P>
<li>
Longtime Texas Rep. E. &quot;Kika&quot; de la Garza announced
Dec. 18 he will not run for a 15th term in the House next year,
saying he felt it was time to serve the public from a different
venue.
<P>
&quot; I feel I can continue outside
of elective office to make a contribution,&quot; de la Garza told
a crowd assembled at the Mission, Tex., Chamber of Commerce building.
<P>
&quot;Helping people is in my
blood and this will never change,&quot; he said. &quot;There are
many more things I would like to do and I want to do them while
I am in good health and young enough--so now is the time.&quot;
<P>
De la Garza, who was first elected
to Congress in 1964, is the ranking Democrat on the House Agriculture
Committee.
<P>
He joined several other House
Democrats who have this year stated their intentions to beat a
path to retirement as the party adjusts to minority status in
the House and Senate for the first time in 40 years.
<P>
De la Garza told the crowd he
believed 1996 would likely be a watershed in the Congress, as
the battle over the balanced budget is likely to continue well
into this year.
<P>
The congressman, now 68, estimated
it would take all his effort and energy to join that fight.
<P>
&quot;We will work to reduce the
deficit, balance the budget, and at the same time protect Medicare,
Medicaid, health, education, and basic programs for the poor and
elderly,&quot; he said about what will be his last year in Congress.
<P>
&quot;I feel I have to devote
all my energies to this effort and cannot let a campaign detract
from it,&quot; de la Garza said.
<P>
The Republicans now enjoy a 236-197
advantage in the House, with the chamber's one independent, Rep.
Bernie Sanders of Vermont, frequently voting with the Democrats.
<BR>

<P>
<li>
Rep. Walter Tucker III resigned rather than face expulsion after
his conviction on extortion and tax evasion charges, but he admitted
no wrongdoing.
<P>
The second-term Democrat said
in a Dec. 12 letter to several officials that he &quot;unfortunately
was not judged by a jury of my peers and in my opinion, did not
receive a just verdict.&quot;
<P>
However, Tucker said, &quot;itwas never my intention to put the Congress through a vote on expulsion
if I were convicted.&quot;
<P>
Tucker, 38, said his resignation
was effective Dec. 15. Gov. Pete Wilson has called for a special
election on March 26 (same day as the primary elections).
<P>
After announcing his resignation,
Tucker endorsed his wife Robin as his successor. He called his
wife the &quot;person who I know will help this community unify&quot;
and said she has the &quot;heart of the community.&quot; 
<P>
Robin Tucker said her agenda would
include &quot;intensifying efforts to make the 37th District's
streets safer; protecting Medicare, Medicaid and Social Security
benefits, and improving economic conditions.&quot; She said, &quot;I
am ready to fight for this community, I am ready to stand for
this community, because I know there is something better for this
community.&quot; 
<P>
But Royce Esters, head of the
Compton branch of the NAACP, &quot;dismissed the announcement&quot;:
&quot;We need to get people who are qualified to run for these
offices. They are trying to keep it in the family. Is that the
answer to Compton's problems?&quot;
<P>
Tucker was elected in 1992 to
represent the working-class communities of Compton, Watts, Carson
and part of Long Beach in southern Los Angeles County.
<P>
He was convicted of extorting
$30,000 in bribes while mayor of Compton to support a proposed
$250 million waste-to-energy project. Tucker, who is black and
a nondenominational minister, has claimed he was entrapped by
the government because of his race and his Christian beliefs.
<P>
He is expected to be sentenced
March 18 to a few years in prison, although he faces a maximum
of 146 years and $1.9 million in fines.<BR>

<P>
<li>
A record 32 candidates--28 Democrats and four Republicans--filed
by the Dec. 26 deadline to succeed Rep. Kweisi Mfume (D), who
is resigning effective Feb. 15 to head up the NAACP.
<P>
The field includes state Sens.
Delores Kelley (D) and Nathaniel McFadden (D); Dels. Clarence
Davis (D), Elijah Cummings (D), Salima Mariott (D) and Kenneth
Montague Jr. (D), plus several clergy members, including Baltimore
City Register of Wills Mary Conaway (D) and Rev. Frank Reid III
(D), who leads a 10,000-member church and is the brother-in-law
of Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke (D). 
<P>
The seat has historically been
held by a resident of West Baltimore City, but with a large field
and redistricting that extended the congressional district further
into East Baltimore and Baltimore Co., nothing is certain. 
<P>
The only major candidate with
ties to Baltimore Co.--where nearly a third of the vote lies--is
Kelly. Mfume said he did not think he would make an endorsement.
The special primary is scheduled for Mar. 5.<BR>

<P>
<li>
Freshman state Sen. Henry Stallings II (D) will run for the seat
held by embattled Rep. Barbara-Rose Collins (D-Mich.). Collins,
a former state House representative and Detroit City Council member
who replaced labor activist George Crockett in Congress, has served
Michigan's 15th Congressional District since 1990.
<P>
Detroit analyst Mario Morrow said
the 56-year-old Collins may be ripe for defeat, noting a House
Ethnics Committee investigation into how she has spent office,
campaign and scholarship funds.
<P>
The Aug. 6 primary is tantamount
to winning election in the heavily Democrat district. Other announced
Democrats include Detroit attorney Godfrey Dillard. The filing
deadline is May 13. </ul>
<P><P>
<center>[ <a href="/nmp/">Headway Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ] </center></BODY>

