<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  January 1996 -- Headway</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>

<tr>

<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="/nmp/wlogo.gif"> </td>

</tr></table>

<p><h3>January 1996</h3><p>

<img src= "/nmp/red-line.gif">

</center><p>



<a name="table"><b>Table of Contents</b></a>

<p>

<ul>

<li><a href="#mfume">Kweisi Mfume Chosen to Head NAACP</a>
<li><a href="#jackson">Jesse Jackson, Jr.</a> Elected to House of Representatives
<li><a href="schr">Patricia Schroeder Announces Retirement<a/>
<li>Debating the <a href="#tx">Vothing Rights Act</a> in Texas
</ul>

<P>

<hr>
<P>

<a name="mfume"></a>
<LI>Rep. Kweisi Mfume was chosen Dec. 9 to head the NAACP, after
15 months during which the nation's oldest civil rights organization
became better known for controversy than activism.
<P>
The Maryland Democrat, who said he will leave Congress in mid-February,
said his first order of business would be to address the organization's
$3.2 million debt and change the group's administrative structure.
<P>
&quot;We're not going to sit by and watch the world change,&quot;
the former head of the Congressional Black Caucus said. &quot;We
are going to change.&quot; Mfume also said that, under his leadership,
the group would begin to place more emphasis on &quot;personal
responsibility.&quot;
<P>
Elected by the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People's board in a unanimous vote, Mfume said he would seek to
cut the size of the board.
<P>
The board has been criticized for being too large and too politicized
and the organization now has more board members than staff members.
<P>
In the past, executive directors have clashed with the 64-member
board over the extent of their power, and potential candidates
for the position have blamed the board for scaring them away.
<P>
But Mfume said one of the conditions he had demanded when he agreed
to take the job was that he report to the board's 17-member executive
committee rather than the entire panel.
<P>
&quot;It is easier to assemble 17 than 64 on any given day,&quot;
Mfume said. His title will be president and chief executive officer,
reflecting his desire for more autonomy.
<P>
Mfume said he would meet with Chairwoman Myrlie Evers-Williams
to come up with a short-term and long-term financial plan.
<P>
He said that plan would include reopening the stream of donations
from corporate donors, approaching potential
<P>
individual donors such as athletes and actors for support, and
trying to increased the ranks of the NAACP's 500,000 members.
<P>
Mfume's broad-minded yet principled style could breathe much needed
life and energy into this 90-year-old group.
<P>
Mfume said he hoped his decision to leave a safe seat in Congress
for the leadership of the NAACP would encourage people to return
to the organization.
<P>
&quot;That example might say to other people that it's all right
to come back home,&quot; he said.
<P>
Many of the organization's larger donors withdrew their support
last year after allegations of financial impropriety were leveled
at former executive director Benjamin Chavis and former chairman
William Gibson.
<P>
Chavis was fired in August 1994 for committing more than $330,000
in NAACP funds without the board's approval to settle a sex discrimination
suit filed against him.
<P>
Gibson, a South Carolina dentist, was ousted in February after
accusations he double-dipped on expenses. An audit released this
summer questioned more than $112,000 in expenses he charged to
the NAACP.
<P>
The resulting drop in donations worsened the NAACP's financial
situation and forced the temporary layoff of most of the national
staff.
<P>
The NAACP now has only 50 national employees, less than half what
it had when Chavis took office.
<P>
Critics had said the search for Chavis' replacement took so long
because of a lack of qualified candidates interested in the job.
<P>
But Evers-Williams, the widow of slain civil rights leader Medgar
Evers, denied that, saying the search was not initiated in earnest
until last May when the search committee was appointed.
<P>
&quot;A search process, if it's done well, tends to take time,&quot;
she said.
<P>
The appointment will allow Evers-Williams a chance to withdraw
from the day-to-day running of the organization.
<P>
The chairmanship is a volunteer position and Evers-Williams has
performed many of the duties Mfume will assume since her appointment
in February, just three days before the death of her second husband,
Walter Williams.
<P>
&quot;I haven't had a chance to mourn my husband,&quot; she said.
&quot;I haven't stopped and it's been very difficult&quot;
<a name="jackson"></a>
<LI>Jesse Jackson, Jr. won a special congessional election Dec.
12 in Chicago to fill the seat vacated by Mel Reynolds, who quit
after being convicted of having sex with an underage campaign
worker. His victory followed his win of the Democratic nomination
Nov. 28.
<P>
The younger Jackson has tried to avoid comparisons with his famous
father during his run for Congress, insisting his campaign is
based on the issues and concerns of Illinois' 2nd District
<P>
But he acknowledged his lineage during a victory speech following
the Nov. 28 special primary election, saying his path to Washington
was paved by his father's life work.
<P>
Jackson said when he was born March 11, 1965, his father was marching
in Selma, AL.
<P>
&quot;He nearly named me Selma. He was caught up in the history
of the moment,&quot; Jackson told an amused throng. &quot;Thank
God for Mama.&quot;
<P>
 He said his early experiences in the areas of voting, public
policy, education and religion became a &quot;part of the foundation
of my being.&quot;
<P>
&quot;Dad never stopped registering voters. . .he never stopped
lifting the hopes of the people.&quot;
<P>
Jackson, 30, beat political veteran Emil Jones, 60, in the Democratic
primary to win the nomination. Voter turnout was a scant 20 percent.
<P>
Before the candidate made his remarks, an uncharacteristically
restrained Rev. Jesse Jackson Sr. praised God for his son's nomination
and led a prayer session.
<P>
Jackson Jr. then took the podium to chants of &quot;Jesse Jr.&quot;
from hundreds of supporters and read a prayer in both English
and Spanish. He then pledged to work for the well-being of the
district's youth.
<P>
Jackson said he ran a forthright campaign, adhering to his lessons
from the Scripture.
<P>
Jackson, a lawyer and field director for the National Rainbow
Coalition, based his campaign on bringing jobs to the area, getting
behind Republican Gov. Jim Edgar's effort to build a third Chicago
area airport at Peotone, about 40 miles southwest of downtown
Chicago.
<P>
Jones, president of the Illinois Senate, urged voters to select
him because of his political experience despite voter sentiment,
nationwide, against career politicians.
<P>
Jones, who relied heavily on Democratic precinct workers in conducting
his campaign, said Jackson's name recognition was an obstacle
that could not be overcome.
<P>
Jackson acknowledged the criticism surrounding his lack of experience
and relative youth.
<P>
Jackson will spend only three months in Congress before facing
voters again in a March primary prior to the fall 1996 election.
<a name="schr"></a>
<LI>After 23 years of challenging the power structure in the House,
Rep. Patricia Schroeder (D-Colo.) announced Nov. 29 she will retire
at the end of this term, in part because she was afraid of becoming
one of the House members who are carried out in a &quot;box.&quot;
<P>
Schroeder said she first thought about retiring from the House
in 1994, but is glad she struck it out for another term because
&quot;it's been important to see the Democratic Party come alive
again. I felt I was needed this year.&quot;
<P>
The former pilot, who was elected to the House at age 32, said
she has not decided what she will do in the future, but it involved
teaching, writing or working for a foundation.
<P>
Schroeder said she anticipates a Democrat can win the liberal-leaning
district covering most of eastern Denver. &quot;If I thought the
Democrats could not hold that seat, believe me, I would not be
here today. Democrats can clearly hold that seat,&quot; she said.
Denver attorney Joe Rogers, a 31-year-old black Republican who
supports abortion rights and affirmative action, announced this
month he would challenge Schroeder in the district, which gave
President Clinton 55 percent of the vote in 1992, and former President
Bush only 39 percent.
<P>
But even without Schroeder as a target, Rogers said in an interview
that the theme of his campaign will be a &quot;new generation
of leadership.&quot; He said he already has an organization of
more than 800 volunteers and expects his campaign war chest to
top $150,000 by the end of this year. &quot;This is going to be
a good fight,&quot; said Rogers, who happened to be across the
street from the U.S. Capitol at the National Republican Congressional
Campaign committee when the word came over CNN that Schroeder
was retiring. &quot;I was totally surprised,&quot; he said. Thus
far, two Democrats have said they would definitely enter the race:
State Rep. Glinda Swanson Lyle and Peter Groff, an official in
Denver Mayor Wellington Webb's administration.
<P>
Three other state representatives, all attorneys, have expressed
interest in the seat: Ken Gordon, Doug Friednash and Diana DeGette.
<P>
Denver City Councilwoman Ramona Martinez, who is currently running
for the open Colorado Senate seat in a crowded field of Democrats,
may jump into the House race as well.
<P>
<a name="tx"></a>
<LI>The state of Texas and the Clinton administration argued before
the Supreme Court Dec. 5 that the majority-black and majority
Hispanic congressional districts in Houston and Dallas are constitutional
because the primary consideration in drawing those districts was
to protect incumbent House members--not to elect blacks or Hispanics
to Congress. At issue are the majority-black seats of Democratic
Reps. Sheila Jackson Lee and Eddie Bernice Johnson, and the majority
Hispanic seat of Democratic Rep. Gene Green. While a 1995 Supreme
Court decision on the Georgia congressional district map said that race
cannot be the predominant factor in drawing districts, the court
was reviewing two more congressional maps--Texas and North Carolina-to
more clearly define the standards.
<P>
The potential stakes are enormous. Justice Stephen G. Breyer said
thousands of federal, state and local elections could some day
be affected by the court's decision, expected by July.
<P>
The 1965 Voting Rights Act says election districts can be unlawful
if they deny minorities the opportunity to elect candidates of
their choice.
<P>
But in 1993, the Supreme Court ruled in a North Carolina case
that districts designed to help minority voters may violate white
voters' rights. Last June, the court ruled in a Georgia case that
such election districts must be presumed unlawful if race was
the main factor in creating them.
<P>
Lower courts struck down three urban congressional districts in
Texas but upheld North Carolina's 12-district map.
<P>
Now, the justices must decide whether race was the predominant
factor in creating those districts, and if so, whether such consideration
was justified by an overwhelmingly important reason.
<P>
Texas Assistant Attorney General Javier Aguilar argued the Texas
districts are constitutional because the lines were motivated
by a state legislature wanting to protect incumbents. Aguilar
said that if political considerations were the core motive or
predominant factor in drawing the lines, then racial considerations
by default could not be the predominant factor--thus making the
districts constitutional, even though race was used as a consideration
when drawing the lines.
<P>
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who held the swing vote in the Georgia
case, asked Aguilar if his argument meant the state legislature
could exclude blacks from majority-white districts in order to
protect a white incumbent who told the mapmakers that blacks would
not vote for him. Deputy Solicitor-General Paul Bender, representing
the administration, later told O'Connor that Democratic map drawers
&quot;weren't looking for black voters--they were looking for
Democratic voters,&quot; and that type of political gerrymandering
is constitutional. But since these districts are labeled &quot;black&quot;
districts or &quot;Hispanic&quot; districts, it appears that the
incumbent argument holds little weight. 
</ul>
<P><P>
<center>[ <a href="/nmp/home.html">Headway Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ] </center></BODY>

