<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  November 1995</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>November 1995</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>

<a name="table"><b>Table of Contents</b></a>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Verdict Still Out on <a href="#mmm">Million Man March</a>
<li>Another <a href="#comm">Presidential Commission on Race Relations?</a>
<li><a href="#powell">OJ Verdict's Impact</a> on Powell's Potential Presidency
<li><a href="#chicago">Special Election</a> in Chicago
<li><a href="#ga">Louisiana's</a> Gubernatorial Race
</ul>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<p><a name="mmm"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p><ul><li>The Million Man March spearheaded by Nation of Islam
Minister Louis Farrakhan and Benjamin Chavis, former executive
director of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, is now in the history books.
<P>
According to U.S. Park Police, a throng of 400,000 mostly black
men filled the Capitol lawn and beyond on Oct. 16, making it the
fourth-largest demonstration in Washington, D.C. history. March
organizers, however, dispute the government's figures, and plan
to file a lawsuit to get the figures corrected to, what they believe,
is closer to one million.
<P>
It is always difficult to gauge large crowd figures such as these,
but, from appearances, it seems that the march organizers are
probably correct that the figure was underestimated.
<P>
At any rate, the massive showing of black men who attended for
various reasons--nearly all of them positive--heartened supporters
and convinced many skeptics that, even with the presence of Farrakhan,
much more was gained than lost.
<P>
Most black conservatives did not support the march initially,
precisely because of the controversial Muslim leader's involvement
and the potential for increased racial division as a result of
the march. But, it appears that most of them were swayed, not
by Farrakhan, but by the sincerity and purpose of the men who
participated in the historical event.
<P>
&quot;You can denounce Farrakhan until the cows come home, but
you cannot argue with the fact of how he has improved the quality
of lives of men in these inner cities--something that the churches
have not done for quite some time,&quot; said syndicated radio
talk showhost Armstrong Williams during a FOX Morning News interview the
morning
following the march. &quot;We all can be better people as a result
of what happened, because it was very peaceful--and I think it
will make a difference in this country.&quot;
<P>
The real test of the march's success, however, will be what takes
place in communities across the country in coming weeks and months.
March participants vowed to go back to their neighborhoods as
more responsible and committed citizens, registering their friends
and families to vote and being more determined to give something
back.
<P>
If they do, indeed, get more involved in uplifting their communities,
it will be reflected in decreased crime figures, increased education
rates and the formation of more intact families.
<P>
Interestingly, since the march, the mainstream media has been
scratching their collective heads to determine whether Farrakhan
is now the leader of black Americans. As has been the rule in
the past, they appear obsessed with selecting one individual as
the leader of all black people, perhaps because this means they
only have to interview one person when they want to know what
&quot;black America thinks.&quot;
<P>
They just don't get it. Blacks are just as diverse in their opinions
as are other groups and one single leader will not suffice.
<P>
<p><a name="comm"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p><LI>Before the ink was dry on stories concerning the march,
liberals were quick to call for yet another presidential commission on race
relations. The request, which was in the form of a letter to President
Clinton, was signed by a well-meaning, but misguided, bipartisan
cast: Democrats Charles Schumer and Charles Rangel of New York,
John Lewis of Georgia, and Eleanor Holmes Norton of the District
of Columbia, and Republicans James Leach of Iowa and Bill McCollum
of Florida.
<P>
Many references have been made to the Kerner Commission report
which revealed (surprise, surprise!) that the nation was moving
toward two separate, unequal white and black societies. The commission
was created by President Lyndon Johnson after several urban riots
in 1968.
<P>
Politicians tend to call for commissions on subjects with which
they prefer not to handle directly. By getting a commission to
study the problem, they can appear to be doing something without
actually doing anything.
<P>
In the 1960s, liberals spent federal funds to find out what any
thinking person on the street could have told them: Our country
began as two separate nations-one based on slavery and the other
based on ownership. To have an expensive government study tell
us the obvious is not only wasteful, but absurd. What we need
to find out is how do we pull it all together, and neither a study
nor a poll can give us the answers.
<P>
As is typical of liberal ideology, rather than deal with the problem,
let's spend the taxpayers' money to find out what we already know.
What America needs is not more studies, but better national leadership
that can not only facilitate a national discussion, but can do
so without scapegoating or patronizing blacks, and without making
whites feel guilt-ridden about a past they cannot change.
<P>
The only thing any of us can change are the present and the future.
As we examine the cast of potential presidents, the ability to
unify the nation should be at or near the top of the list of qualifications.
<P>
Before the establishment of such a commission is even considered,
the American public has the right to know: Who will conduct the
study and what will be their premise? And, more important, how
much will it cost?
<P><p><a name="powell"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<LI>Colin Powell's potential presidential candidacy may be
impacted by the not-guilty verdict in the O.J. Simpson trial,
but analysts differ as to whether that impact will be positive
or negative. Commenting on the verdict shortly after it was announced,
Powell said &quot;The trial showed the judicial system works.&quot;
<P>
He prefaced his remarks by saying, &quot;I don't know that we
should go into a huge national debate about this. We've got to
move on.&quot;
<P>
But he went on tot say &quot;that the different reactions to the
trial from blacks and whites is something 'we should not walk
away and forget about.'&quot;
<P>
&quot;It should be troubling not to me but to all America that
there is still polarization,&quot; said Powell. &quot;The same
America that gave 'an incredible opportunity to me as a black'
still leaves many citizens trapped by their circumstance.&quot;
<P>
GOP consultant Eddie Mahe says, &quot;It will increase the great
healer-a role that is exquisitely difficult for him or anyone
else to fill.&quot; And Democratic consultant Tad Devine says
&quot;this could be a golden chance for Powell.&quot; &quot;Voting
for a black candidate can be a tremendous act of self-affirmation
for white voters, if there is a black candidate whose values they
share,&quot; said Devine.
<P>
A GOP strategist, however, was reportedly spreading the idea that
this undermines the case for Powell candidacy since whites will
now be less likely to vote for a black candidate. Some black analysts
were also skeptical.
<P>
&quot;Whatever he says-even if he splits the difference-he's going
to lose something on both sides. . .This may be a
defining moment for him,&quot; said Howard University political
science chairman Ronald Walters, on Powell and the verdict.
<P>
Washington Post columnist Mary McGrory wrote that &quot;one of
the many consequences of the earthquake verdict is that people
talk of beseeching [Powell] to lead them over the chasm.&quot;
But CNN political analyst Bill Schneider disagreed: &quot;When
racial polarization intensifies, it hurts Democrats and it helps
Republicans, unless Republicans are seen as creating it or exploiting
it.&quot;
<P><p><a name="chicago"></A>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<LI> With former Rep. Mel Reynolds (D-Il.) beginning a five-year
sentence for sexual misconduct, 14 candidates--10 Democrats and
4 Republicans--met the OCL 9 filing deadline in preparation for
the Nov. 28 special primary and Dec. 12 general election.
<P>
As for the primary, Senate Minority Leader Emil Jones is viewed
by many as an early favorite. Jones has the backing of Chicago's
infamous Democratic machine and, thus, his name will appear atop
the Democratic ballot. Jones has been endorsed by local party
officials and has long ties to Mayor Richard Daley.
<P>
However, State Sen. Alice Palmer is giving Jones a run for his
money (see &quot;Featured Politico&quot; interview ). She has
received the endorsement of a group of African-American men of
various religious, social, economic and political backgrounds.
They stated that the 2nd Congressional District will be &quot;politically
safe under her leadership,&quot; and urged all prospective candidates
to join them in supporting Palmer.
<P>
All the leading Democratic candidates appeared at an Oct. 9 debate.
Calling himself the &quot;voice of a new generation,&quot; attorney
Jesse Jackson, Jr. reportedly displayed some of the rhetorical
flair of his famous father.
<P>
&quot;I'm tired of Monty Hall politics: Let's make a deal,&quot;
said the younger Jackson. &quot;We can't stop the importation
of $200 billion worth of drugs into our country, but we can stop
one cigar coming in from Cuba.&quot;
<P>
But it will take more than homilies and witticisms for Jackson
to break out of the pack. He carries both the baggage and the
connections of his father, who, despite having a genius for espousingcolorful rhetoric, has yet to be elected to any post other than
that of the largely symbolic D.C. &quot;shadow&quot; senator.
<P>
During the debate, Palmer spoke out against casino gambling and
reductions in Medicaid funding, while stressing that her campaign
is about mobilizing people.
<P>
State Rep. Monique Davis promised to hold regular town meetings.
She was endorsed by former Rep. Gus Savage, whom Reynolds defeated
in 1992. Savage's 12-year career in the House was riddled with
charges of absenteeism, blatant incomplete campaign finance disclosure
statements, nepotism, sexual harassment and bigotry against whites
generally and Jews specifically.
<P>
No Republican has won the seat since 1950.
<P>
The 2nd Congressional District includes much of Chicago's old
South Side industrial area plus many suburbs to the south. About
two-thirds of its people live in Chicago, in widely separated
neighborhoods. Two-thirds of the district's voters are black,
and most are middle-class.
<P><p><a name="ga"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<LI>Rep. Bill Jefferson (D-La.) quit the Louisiana governor's
race Sept. 19 and threw his support to fellow Rep. Cleo Fields
(D-La.) In return, Fields pledged to support Jefferson in next
year's open Senate race to succeed retiring Sen. Bennett Johnston
(D).
<P>
Jefferson's decision was seen as a big step toward solidifying
the state's black vote-about 28 percent of Louisiana's registered
voters-and thereby increase the chances of a black candidate making
the gubernatorial runoff.
<P>
The field for the Oct. 21 governor's election drops to 16 candidates,
all of whom appear on the same ballot, regardless of party. Should
no candidate win a majority, there will be a Nov. 18 runoff between
the two top finishers. What will be the effect of Jefferson's
pullout? Here's a look at the most
 recent poll of the governor's race:
<P><PRE>
 Ex. Gov. Buddy Roemer 		(R)	33%
 Treasurer Mary Landrieu 	(D)	13%
 Lt. Gov. Melinda Schwegmann 	(D)	12%
 Rep. Cleo Fields 		(D)	8%
 State Sen. Mike Foster 	(R)	6%	
 Rep. Bill Jefferson 		(D)	5%
 Undecided/Other			23%
    
   Source: Mason Dixon Poll conducted Aug. 25-28, 1995.
</Pre>
<P><P>
</ul><center>[ <a href="/nmp/home.html">NMP Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ] </center></BODY>

