<p>

<img src="red-line.gif">
<h3>June 1995</h3>
</center>
<p>
<h3><a name="quick">QuickLinks</a></h3>
<A HREF="#district">
Challanges to congressional districts designed to elect African-Americans</A><br>

<A HREF="#dc">Washington D.C. as Maryland's 9th congressional disctrict?</A><br>
<A HREF="#affirmative">
Clinton defends blacks-only scholarships at the University of Maryland.</A><br>
<A HREF="#pac">Black business executives seek to eliminate or modify affirmative action programs
</A><p>
<hr><a name="districts"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>

The Supreme Court heard arguments in two cases-one in Georgia and one in Louisiana in which
the configuration of congressional districts designed to elect African-Americans is being
challenged.  Georgia's I 1th congressional district, represented by Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D),
and Louisiana's 4th congressional district, represented by Rep. Gleo Fields (D), were-both
"drawn to concentrate black voters."<p>

Three-judge panels  in both states ruled last t year that the 11 district-drawing state legislators
"had effectively disenfranchised whites." critics of the districts also claim that they isolate black
voters and result in the creation of other districts more likely to elect Republicans.<p>

"At some point, it's a violadon of the US. Constitution to design (political districts) . . . based on
race," said Judge Anthony Kennedy. The districts were drawn specificaily to be "safe" for black
candidates.<p>

Georgia's 11th District stretches 250 miles, "with finger-like hooks scooping up black voters in
Atlanta, Augusta and Savannah" It is 64 percent black. The <i>Monroe (La.) News Star</i>
described Louisiana's 4th District as "a racial seat-belt, slashing diagonally from the state's
northwest corner to the 'waist' where the state line leaves the Mississippi River." It is about 61
percent black.<p>

"It is not an overstatement to say that the Supreme Court's decision in the cases argued today will
likely determine the shape of AmeAcan politics into the 21st century," said National Public
Radio's Nina Totenberg.  For the court's decision in these cases will likely determine the rules for
redistricting all over the country and not just at the federal level, but at the state and local level
too."<p>

An Atlanta Journal editorial also included comments on the Supreme Court's deliberations. "Our
hope is that it will send the case back to the states and require them to redraw lines on a basis
other than race. It should also insist that the Justice Department reaffirrn the original intent of the
Voting Rights Act: Guarantee the right to vote to all, but guarantee a racial outcome to
none."<p>

<hr><a name="dc"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich is researching a plan that gives District of Columbia residents full
voting representation in Congress as Marylanders. The plan, which still is in the "idea" stage,
would make the District of Columbia Maryland's 9th congressional district for federal voting
purposes only.<p>

District of Columbia residents would vote to elect a "full-fledged" congress member and would
cast votes for Maryland'stwosenators. D.C. would retain its own mayor and council, and would
not vote for governor or any other state offices in Maryland.<p>

"It's a great idea as an interim step to full statehood," said D.C. Mayor Marion Barry (D), on
Gingrich's proposal. But Maryland Republicans oppose the plan because "it would bring an
influx of Dernocrats into the race for U.S. Senate seats."<p>

Maryland GOP Chair Joyce Terhes said, "Our chances of getting a Republican senator would be
almost nil. That's a general concern . . . It's more a question of the mechanics of how to make it
work: That they would participate in congressional elections but not other elections to me just
doesn't make sense."<p>

Registered Democrats outnumber registered Republicans "by more than 10 to 1 in the city, which
has 367,013 voters, 289,353 of whom are Democrat" Maryland House Minority Leader Robert
Kittleman (R): "Our last race for governor was almost a tie, and we might have a chance in the
Senate next time. Hang that noose around our neck and everyone will just give up."<p>

"What the speaker is proposing would take a constitudonal amendment," said D.C. Delegate
Eleanor Holmes Norton through a spokesperson. "What he could do now is return the delegate's
right to vote on the basis of residents of the District of Columbia paying federal income
taxes."<p>

But Gingrich's proposal is just one of several ideas being brandied about on Capitol Hill to give
the District a voice in Congress. Maryland Democrat Senators Barbara Mikulski and Paul
Sarbanes support full statehood for District of Columbia.<p>

<p>
<hr><a name="affirmative"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>

In the midst of its review of affirmative action programs, the Clinton administration defended the use of blacks-only scholarships at the University of Maryland.<p>

In a brief filed the first week of May with the Supreme Court, the administration argued in
support of racebased scholarships used to correct previous segregation at the university's College
Park campus.<p>

It did not address the larger issue of using such scholarships to diversify a school if
discrimination had not been proven.<p>

 The administration's action suggests that scholarships similar to the one in question would
survive the sweeping White House review of affirmadve action. Administration officials
caudoned against such speculations, however.<p>

"The Jusdce Department's decision to enter into the University of Maryland case is completely
separate from the internal and ongoing review that the White House is conducdng on affinnadve
action programs," Ginny Terzano, a White House spokeswoman, said May 3.<p>

The brief filed by Solicitor General Drew S. lVays on May I supports the university's appeal of a
decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit in Richmond, Va.<p>

The court ruled in favor of a Hispanic student who said the university violated his constitutional
rights when it denied him a scholarship limited to black students.<p>

The appeals court said the university had failed to prove the scholarship was necessary to correct
lingering effects of segregation When the lawsuit was filed in 1990, the campus' snzdent body
was 11.2 percent black.<p>

The Clinton administration argued that the court should have presumed the racial disparity was
the result of the campus's long history of segregation. The burden would then be on the student,
Daniel J. Podberesky, to prove otherwise.<p>

The university created the Benjamin Banneker Scholarship Program under pressure from the
federal government, which sought to compel desegregation of the College Park campus.<p>

The campus was limited to whites only by law until the mid-19SOs. Segregadon lingered there
unofficially into the late 1970s.<p>

The  university also had scholarships to attract white students to its traditionally black campuses,
and scholarships open to students of all races.<p>

The campus usually awards at least 20 Banneker scholarships each year, covering fouryears of
tuition, room and board They account for about I percent of the College Park campus' annual
financial aid budget.<p>

 Although former Pennsylvania Governor Robert Casey has bowed out of the 1996 presidendal race, he will "continue to hound" President Clinton and other fellow
Democrats by setting up a group to elect pro-life candidates.<p>

Casey adviser Jeffrey Bell said the ex-governor is establishing a political action committee, a
private foundadon and a lobbying organizadon, "all dedicated to furthering family issues." He
added that the orl anizations are expeckd to receive funding from some of the political donors
who pledged Casey $500,000 for his presidendal race.<p>

The Casey polidcal action committee will help fund the candidacies of federal and state
Democrats who are at odds with the party's pro-choice posidons.<p>

"There's no cessadon in the game plan," said Casey. "It's going to be executed exactly as before,
except instead of being a candidate, I'm going to be pushing all three buttons." Bell noted that
while Republicans have their own organizations for promoting prolife candidates, "pro life
Democrats feel excluded from the party."<p>

<hr><a name="pac"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
 A group of black business executives said May 10 that they were forming a political action committee and hiring a lobbyist to fight efforls to eliminate or modify affirmative action
programs, including those that set aside a percentage of government contracts for
minority-owned companies, according to a report in The New York Times.<p>

"Undl now, the voice of black business has been largdy silent on the twin issues of affirmative
action and minority set asides," said Earl G. Graves, publisher and founder of Black Enterprise
magazine, at a news conference.<p>

Graves, who was joined by other black executives, said that the group was "drawing a line in the
sand" and that there would be "no retreat" on affirmative action. The gnup is made up of the
Black Enterprise 100, the largest blackowned companies in the U.S.<p>

"Until we get to the point in this country where there is truly a level playing field," said Maceo
Sloan, head of the Sloan Financial Group, "where a black business can go to a bank, for example,
and be judged, in terms of loans, on the same basis that the majority businesses in this county are
judged; where we have the same access to capital that they have and where there truly is a level playing field, we will very vigorously oppose the effort that is going on right now to
eliminate all the affirmadve action programs."<p>

Earlier this year, Congress voted to end a tax break for companies that sell television stations and
cable systems to minorities. The program came under intense criticism as a result of a proposed
sale by Viacom Inc., a New Yorkbased media giant, to a group of investors headed by Frank
Washington, a black entrepreneur from California.<p>

Critics of the sale said it was an affirmative action program intended to help minority
millionaires.<p>

But at the news conference the black executdves said that such criticism reflected a double
standard because there are several federal programs, like farm subsidies, that help wealthy
individuals and businesses.<p>

"What about all the thousands of millionaires who are majority business owners, and no one
raises the issue of that being un-American?" Graves said. UWhen we start to do it, all of a
sudden, let's change the rules."<p>

Graves said the 100 largest blackowned companies had combined sales of about $11.7 billion
last year and employed about 47,000 people, indicating that if the group could muster its
financial resources, it could have significant political impact.<p>

The executives said they had not yet solicited all the top black businesses to contribute to the
political action committee, which will be called Mobilizadon for Economic Opportunity. But
Graves said he did not think it would be difficult to persuade them to reach into their
pockets.<p>

Whether you talk about L.A or San Francisco, or Chicago, or Detroit, or Atlanta or New York,
the issues are the same," he said. "It would seem to me we're not going to have a very hard
selling point to push here."<p>

Still, with the Republican-controlled Congress aiming for cuts in the federal deficit and a
balanced budget, all programs including farm subsidies, Medicare and what some call "welfare
for the rich" are on the table and subject to reduction or elimination. This may not be the right
year to lobby for maintaining programs which do not have broad-based support among the  American electorate.
<p>
<p>
