<html><head><title>National Minority Politics - From the Publisher - October 1995</title></head><body><h2>From the Publisher</h2><p><h3>NOVEMBER 1995</h3><p><img src="red-line.gif"><p>	Other than political pundits and political junkies, most Americans have not yet turned their attention to the 1996 presidential race. President Clinton will apparently be the Democratic nominee and has shored up his base during the last few months.
<P>
The re-entry of Ross Perot into the election equation with his newly-formed third party--the Independence Party (the Reform Party in some states where there is a name conflict)-has heartened Democrats because it is perceived that Perot takes more potential votes from the political right than he does the political left.
<P>
In polls taken earlier this year, Clinton was losing to a then unnamed Republican presidential opponent. Now he beats the front-runner among GOP candidates, Sen. Robert Dole of Kansas, by several percentage points. Clinton's opponents usually make the mistake of underestimating his political tenacity and dexterity--at their peril. Remember: Former President George Bush was receiving 90 percent approval ratings a year-and-a-half before the 1992 general election.
<P>
There is an obvious yearning among the electorate for a president with leadership abilities, who inspires and presents a vision for the next millennium. Clinton has described the public mood as that of being in a "funk." Some have compared this description to that of President Carter's "malaise" speech during the year leading up to his re-election defeat. But the state of the public's mood runs much deeper. In many ways, Americans are depressed about their future. Media constantly bombard them with bad news--conflict, controversy and grim statistics.
<P>
The political process, including incessant media frenzies, has resulted in the denigration of nearly every American hero, living or dead. They want to tighten their fiscal belts, but depressed wages often keep them from doing the right thing The two major parties often appear to be more interested in making each other look bad, than explaining to voters exactly what is going on.
<P>
What the existing crop of Republican contenders are faced with is high expectations from a cynical public which has been disillusioned by its political leaders in recent years. Dole, et al, are campaigning in this complex environment and do not appear to making much headway.
<P>
Dole, the only candidate who has a significant amount of support from likely Republican primary voters, does not seem to be generating much enthusiasm. His support, at best, is sot The other candidates are registering in single digits with voters in most polls. The only people who seem to be benefiting from the GOP primary process are political consultants, who get paid to spend a candidate's money until it runs out.
<P>
Enter General Colin Powell. So far, he maintains high name identification and respect among the public, the media hasn't yet bloodied him up with stories about past mistakes, and he has not been forced to be about many of the pressing issues of the day. Some people see him as a savior for what ails America; some are not so sure.
<P>
But it is clear from the current political climate that voters are not going to settle for someone who doesn't make them optimistic about the future, someone they can trust, someone they can be proud to call "Mr. President."
<P>
			Willie A. Richardson<br>						Publisher<p>[ <a href="home.html">NMP Home</a> | <a href="i-col.html">Index</a> ]<p></body></html>
