<HTML>
<HEAD><title>Headway - From the Publisher - January 96</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<h2>From the Publisher</h2><p>
<h3>January 1996</h3>
<p><img src="red-line.gif"><p>      
<P>

<P>
This edition of <I>Headway</I> launches a new beginning for our
publication. As our readers know, since its inception in 1988
as a newsletter, our publication has been titled <I>National Minority
Politics</I>. Several months ago, our corporate board of directors,
including the publisher and editor, decided that, as a move toward
expanding the magazine's base and ensuring future growth, we would
change the Publication's name.
<P>
Why a name change and why now, some might ask. The reasons are
varied and numerous. First our name was simply too long for a
magazine title. One-word or two-word titles in the magazine industry
are the general rule, and we wanted to bring our publication in
line with industry standards.
<P>
Second, our name became too much of an issue for some potential
subscribers and advertisers. The term &quot;minority&quot; has
many connotations, most of which, for our purposes, carried more
cons than pros. For example, &quot;minority&quot; usually means
a member of a racial minority, but in today's era of micro-classification,
now almost everyone qualifies as a minority. From a political
standpoint, the term &quot;minority&quot; also implies a liberal,
big government ideology. Because of this, many potential readers
also mistakenly presumed that our publication has a liberal slant,
which it clearly does not.
<P>
Others thought we were a political organization, rather than a
magazine. Still others thought that the magazine was only for
minorities, which is certainly not the case. Our readership is
racially and ethnically diverse, and we have made an effort to
see that it remains so. Without discourse across racial and ethnic
lines, we have no hope of ever solving any of the problems our
nation faces.
<P>
Third, our name was too narrow and confining. Yes, we do primarily
discuss political issues, but not exclusively. Yes, the majority
of our writers are black or Hispanic, but, more importantly, they
are excellent, deliberative thinkers. Labeling them as merely
&quot;minority&quot; writers somehow seemed to diminish their
credentials.
<P>
Finally, we wanted a name which implied that we were looking toward
the future, that we were winning the philosophical battle, that
we were ahead of the curve in presenting ideas on the nation's
most vital issues, that ours is not a racial magazine, but an
ideas magazine. We believe the name <I>Headway</I> does just that.
<P>
But for those who have expressed their preference for our current
format and content, not to worry. There will be no substantial
changes in the format or content. We will be adding a few new
writers and sections, but our approach to the issues--and our
promotion of the ideals of strong families, individual responsibility,
free enterprise and limited government--will remain constant.
<P>
We would like to express our thanks to our staff and writers,
many of whom have been with us since our expansion to a magazine
format. We would also like to thank our committed readers for
their support and for spreading the word about <I>National Minority
Politics</I>. We hope you will continue to be ambassadors for
<I>Headway</I> as well.
<P>
We're looking forward to a successful 1996, and extend the same
wishes to all our readers.
<P>
<center>
Willie A. Richardson<br>                                
                Publisher<p>
[ <a href="/nmp/home.html">Headway Home</a> | <a href="/nmp/i-col.html">Index</a> ]<p></center></body></html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B10-177</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA070-000443-B046-1</DOCOLDNO>
